ory:Romanian people of World War I]]\n[[Category:Burials at Bellu]]\n[[Category:Members of the Romanian Academy elected posthumously]]\n", "name_user": "Iridescent", "label": "safe", "comment": "Cleanup andtypo fixing,typo(s) fixed: 1870-1880 \u2192 1870\u20131880 (4)", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Alexandru_Macedonski"}
{"title_page": "Bob Mann (American football)", "text_new": "{{good article}}\n{{short description|American football wide receiver}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=February 2020}}\n{{Infobox NFL biography\n| image               = 1950 Bowman Bob Mann Yankees.jpg\n| alt                 = A football card showing a portrait of Mann in his blue Yankees jersey\n| caption             = Mann's 1950 [[Bowman Gum|Bowman]] football card\n| number              = 31, 87\n| position            = [[End (gridiron football)|End]]\n| birth_date          = {{Birth date|1924|04|08|mf=y}}\n| birth_place         = [[New Bern, North Carolina]], US\n| death_date          = {{death date and age|2006|10|21|1924|04|8}}\n| death_place         = [[Detroit, Michigan]], US\n| height_ft           = 5\n| height_in           = 11\n| weight_lb           = 172\n| high_school         = {{Ubl|[[J.T. Barber School|J. T. Barber]]|(New Bern, North Carolina, US)}}\n| college             = [[Michigan Wolverines football|Michigan]]\n| undraftedyear       = 1948\n| pastteamsnote       = yes\n| pastteams           = \n* [[Detroit Lions]] ([[1948 NFL season|1948]]\u2013[[1949 NFL season|1949]])\n* [[New York Yankees (AAFC)|New York Yankees]] ([[1950 NFL season|1950]])*\n* [[Green Bay Packers]] ([[1950 NFL season|1950]]\u2013[[1954 NFL season|1954]])\n| highlights          = \n* [[List of NFL annual receiving yards leaders|NFL receiving yards leader]] (1949)\n* [[Green Bay Packers Hall of Fame]]\n* Second-team [[College Football All-America Team|All-American]] ([[1947 College Football All-America Team|1947]])\n* First-team All-[[Big Ten Conference|Big Nine]] ([[1947 All-Big Nine Conference football team|1947]])\n| statlabel1          = Receptions\n| statvalue1          = 208\n| statlabel2          = Receiving yards\n| statvalue2          = 3,203\n| statlabel3          = Receiving touchdowns\n| statvalue3          = 24\n| nfl                 = 2520072\n| pfr                 = MannBo00\n}}\n\n'''Robert Mann''' (April 8, 1924 \u2013 October 21, 2006) was an American [[American football|professional football]] player in the [[National Football League]] (NFL). A native of [[New Bern, North Carolina]], Mann played [[college football]] at [[Hampton University|Hampton Institute]] in 1942 and 1943 and at the [[University of Michigan]] in 1944, 1946 and 1947. Playing the [[End (American football)|end]] position, he broke the [[Big Ten Conference]] record for receiving yardage in 1946 and again in 1947. After going undrafted in the [[1948 NFL Draft]], Mann would sign his first professional football contract with the [[Detroit Lions]], where he played for two seasons. He would later player for the [[Green Bay Packers]] for parts of five seasons until 1954. Mann was the first African American player for both teams.\n\nMann led the NFL in receiving yardage (1,014 yards) and yards per reception (15.4) in 1949. Mann was asked to take a pay cut after the 1949 season and became a hold out when the Lions opened practice in July 1950. He was traded to the [[New York Yankees (AAFC)|New York Yankees]] in August 1950 and released three weeks later. Mann charged that he had been \"railroaded\" out of professional football for refusing to take a pay cut. He signed with the Green Bay Packers near the end of the [[1950 NFL season]] and was the team's leading receiver in 1951. He remained with the Packers through the 1954 season. After his football career, Mann became a lawyer and practiced law in [[Detroit]]. He was inducted into the [[Green Bay Packers Hall of Fame]] in 1988 and died in October 2006 at the age of 82.\n\n==Early years==\nBob Mann was born in [[New Bern, North Carolina|New Bern]], the county seat of [[Craven County, North Carolina]], in 1924.<ref name=NB>{{cite news |last=Bryant|first=Arabelle|title=New Bern's Mann established several sports firsts |newspaper=[[Sun Journal (New Bern, North Carolina)|Sun Journal]]|date=January 16, 2010 |access-date=November 21, 2019 |url=http://www.newbernsj.com/news/mann-59214-bern-new.html |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100119021815/http://www.newbernsj.com/news/mann-59214-bern-new.html |archive-date=January 19, 2010 }}</ref> At the time of his childhood, New Bern was a small town of about 10,000 and was still segregated.<ref name=\"PIONEER\">{{Cite news | first = Bill| last = Dow| title = Mann pioneer player in NFL: Part 2| date = January 11, 2002| access-date = November 22, 2019| url-status=live |newspaper = [[Detroit Free Press]]| page = 8D| url = https://www.newspapers.com/clip/24262964/mann_end_was_one_of_1st_black_lions/| archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20191122153540/https://www.newspapers.com/clip/24262964/mann_end_was_one_of_1st_black_lions/| archive-date = November 22, 2019| via = [[Newspapers.com]]|type=clipping}}</ref> His father, William Mann, was a physician, and his mother, Clara Mann, was a supervisor of Craven County elementary schools. Mann began his football career at West Street High School in New Bern.<ref name=NB/>\n\n==College football==\n\n===Hampton Institute===\nIn 1941, Mann enrolled at Hampton Institute (now known as [[Hampton University]]), a [[Historically black colleges and universities|historically black university]] located in [[Hampton, Virginia]]. He joined the school's [[college football|football]] team, and as a sophomore, he scored 45 of Hampton's 99 points while playing at the left end position. He scored three [[touchdown]]s in Hampton's final game against [[Virginia Union University|Virginia Union]].<ref>{{cite news|title=Bob Mann Scores 45 Points|newspaper=[[Baltimore Afro-American|The Afro American]]|date=December 8, 1942|url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?id=Op4lAAAAIBAJ&sjid=4_QFAAAAIBAJ&pg=2974,6027682&dq=bob-mann&hl=en|access-date=November 21, 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181004145950/https://news.google.com/newspapers?id=Op4lAAAAIBAJ&sjid=4_QFAAAAIBAJ&pg=2974,6027682&dq=bob-mann&hl=en|archive-date=October 4, 2018|url-status=live|via=[[Google News Archive]]|page=23}}</ref>\n\n===University of Michigan===\n[[File:Bob Mann (American football).jpg|thumb|right|Mann posing in the 1947 [[University of Michigan]] yearbook|alt=Mann in his football gear posing as if he is running]]\nMann transferred to Michigan in 1944, with his father hoping that he would attend the school's medical program.<ref name=\"PIONEER\"/> He joined the football team as a [[Walk-on (sports)|walk-on]] and ended up being one of only two [[African-American]] players ([[Gene Derricotte]] was the other) on the [[1944 Michigan Wolverines football team]].<ref name=\"EMBODY\">{{Cite news | first = Charlie| last = Vincent| title = Bob Mann Embodies Sport's Real Lessons| date = February 13, 1988| url-status=live |access-date = November 22, 2019| newspaper = [[Detroit Free Press]]| page = 1D | url = https://www.newspapers.com/clip/24262813/bob_mann_embodies_sports_real_lessons/| archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20191122153227/https://www.newspapers.com/clip/24262813/bob_mann_embodies_sports_real_lessons/| archive-date = November 22, 2019| via = [[Newspapers.com]]|type=clipping}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=1944 Michigan Football Roster |publisher=[[Bentley Historical Library]] |url=http://141.211.39.65/allroster/FMPro?-DB=allrost.fp5&-Format=fbresult.htm&-SortField=name&-SortOrder=Ascend&year=1944&-max=170&-Find |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100819230444/http://141.211.39.65/allroster/FMPro?-DB=allrost.fp5&-Format=fbresult.htm&-SortField=name&-SortOrder=Ascend&year=1944&-max=170&-Find |url-status=dead |archive-date=August 19, 2010 |access-date=November 21, 2019 }}</ref> Mann took a year off for military service, serving in the [[United States Navy|Navy]] during [[World War II]], although he was stationed in [[Staten Island]] and was not deployed overseas.<ref name=\"PIONEER\"/>{{sfn|Piascik|2009|p=38}} After his service, he returned to Michigan in 1946.<ref name=\"PACK\">{{Cite web | first = Cliff | last = Christl | url = https://www.packers.com/news/bob-mann-endured-for-his-opportunity | title = Bob Mann endured for his opportunity | date = September 27, 2018 | access-date = November 22, 2019 | publisher = [[Green Bay Packers, Inc.]] | archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20180927180007/https://www.packers.com/news/bob-mann-endured-for-his-opportunity| archive-date = September 27, 2018| url-status = live}}</ref> \n \nMann started two games at the left end for [[Fritz Crisler]]'s [[1946 Michigan Wolverines football team|1946 Michigan football team]].<ref>{{cite web|title=1946 Football Team|publisher=[[Bentley Historical Library]]|access-date=February 6, 2020|url=https://bentley.umich.edu/athdept/football/fbteam/1946fbt.htm|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190615193345/https://bentley.umich.edu/athdept/football/fbteam/1946fbt.htm|archive-date=June 15, 2019|url-status=live}}</ref> On November 16 against [[1946 Wisconsin Badgers football team|Wisconsin]], he caught three passes for 74 yards and two touchdowns and also gained 26 yards on two [[end-around]] runs.<ref>{{cite news|type=clipping|title=Mention Mann In Lineman Poll|newspaper=[[The Michigan Daily]]|date=November 21, 1946|page=3|url=https://digital.bentley.umich.edu/midaily/mdp.39015071756212/337|via=[[Newspapers.com]]|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200207030730/https://digital.bentley.umich.edu/midaily/mdp.39015071756212/337|archive-date=February 6, 2020}}</ref> And against [[1946 Ohio State Buckeyes football team|Ohio State]] the following week, he caught five passes for 101 yards and two touchdowns and added 33 yards on two end-around plays.<ref>{{cite news | title = Michigan Routs OSU But Misses Crown: Part 1 | newspaper = [[The Michigan Daily]] | first = Clark | last = Baker | date = November 24, 1946 | pages = 1 | url = https://digital.bentley.umich.edu/midaily/mdp.39015071756212/353 | via = [[Bentley Historical Library]] | url-status = live | archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20200206201839/https://digital.bentley.umich.edu/midaily/mdp.39015071756212/353 | archive-date = February 6, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite news | title = Michigan Routs OSU But Misses Crown: Part 2 | newspaper = [[The Michigan Daily]] | first = Clark | last = Baker | date = November 24, 1946 | pages = 6 | url = https://digital.bentley.umich.edu/midaily/mdp.39015071756212/358 | via = [[Bentley Historical Library]] | url-status = live | archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20200211194413/https://digital.bentley.umich.edu/midaily/mdp.39015071756212/358 | archive-date = February 11, 2020}}</ref> Despite seeing only limited action, his 1946 total of 13 receptions for 284 receiving yards set a new [[Big Ten Conference]] record.<ref>{{Cite news | last = Smith | first = Wilfrid | title = Colleges Have Greatest Year for Football: Part 1 | newspaper = [[Chicago Tribune]] | date = December 22, 1946| page = Part 2, Page 1 | url = https://www.newspapers.com/clip/44052058/colleges_have_greatest_year_for/ | via = [[Newspapers.com]] | url-status = live| archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20200211194008/https://www.newspapers.com/clip/44052058/colleges_have_greatest_year_for/ | archive-date = February 6, 2020 | type = clipping}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news | last = Smith | first = Wilfrid | title = Colleges Have Greatest Year for Football: Part 2 | newspaper = [[Chicago Tribune]] | date = December 22, 1946 | page = Part 2, Page 4 | url = https://www.newspapers.com/clip/43735264/colleges_have_greatest_year_for_football/ | via = [[Newspapers.com]] | url-status = live | archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20200207031749/https://www.newspapers.com/clip/43735264/colleges_have_greatest_year_for_football/ | archive-date = February 11, 2020 | type = clipping}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=Michigan Shifts Mann|newspaper=[[Chicago Tribune]]|page=36|date=September 19, 1947|url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/43735398/michigan_shifts_mann/|via=[[Newspapers.com]]|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200207030914/https://www.newspapers.com/clip/43735398/michigan_shifts_mann/|archive-date=February 6, 2020|url-status=live|type=clipping}}</ref> With 30 points on five touchdowns, Mann was also the second-leading scorer on the 1946 Michigan team, trailing only placekicker [[Jim Brieske]].<ref>{{cite news|title=Michigan Scoring Honors Copped by Two Linemen|newspaper=[[The Michigan Daily]]|first=Alys|last=George|date=November 27, 1946|page=3|url=https://digital.bentley.umich.edu/midaily/mdp.39015071756212/369|via=[[Bentley Historical Library]]|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200207031656/https://digital.bentley.umich.edu/midaily/mdp.39015071756212/369|archive-date=February 6, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> He also gained 114 yards on nine end-around plays in 1946, earning him a nickname as the \"fifth man\" in Michigan's backfield.<ref>{{cite news|title=Wolverines' '5th Back' Set for Spartan Opener|newspaper=[[Detroit Free Press]]|first=Tommy|last=Devine|date=September 25, 1947|page=23|url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/43738658/wolverines_5th_back_set_for_spartan/|via=[[Newspapers.com]]|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200207031012/https://www.newspapers.com/clip/43738658/wolverines_5th_back_set_for_spartan/|archive-date=February 6, 2020|url-status=live|type=clipping}}</ref>\n\nAs a senior, Mann started seven games at left end on Crisler's undefeated [[1947 Michigan Wolverines football team|1947 Michigan team]].<ref name=t47>{{cite web|title=1947 Football Team|publisher=[[Bentley Historical Library]]|url=http://bentley.umich.edu/athdept/football/fbteam/1947fbt.htm|access-date=November 21, 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110724041347/http://bentley.umich.edu/athdept/football/fbteam/1947fbt.htm|archive-date=July 24, 2011|url-status=live}}</ref> He caught 12 passes for 302 yards and three touchdowns and ran for 129 yards on 15 end-around plays.<ref name=Signs/> On October 4, against [[1947 Stanford Cardinal football team|Stanford]], Mann caught a 61-yard touchdown pass from [[Bob Chappuis]] on Michigan's second play of the game.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/39399188/wolverines_grind_out_4913_victory_over/|title=Wolverines Grind Out 49-13 Victory Over Stanford|newspaper=[[The Cincinnati Enquirer]]|page=42|url-status=live|date=October 5, 1947|via=[[Newspapers.com]]|type=clipping|agency=[[Associated Press]]|access-date=November 21, 2019|archive-date=November 21, 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191121223636/https://www.newspapers.com/clip/39399188/wolverines_grind_out_4913_victory_over/}}</ref> Against [[1947 Pittsburgh Panthers football team|Pitt]] the following week, he caught three passes for 105 yards and two touchdowns, including a 70-yard scoring play on a pass from Chappuis.<ref>{{cite news|title=Free Press Turns Grid Spotlight on U-M's Mann, Wistert, C. Elliott|newspaper=[[Detroit Free Press]]|first=Tommy|last=Devine|date=October 14, 1947|page=16|url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/43740259/free_press_turns_grid_spotlight/|via=[[Newspapers.com]]|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200207031202/https://www.newspapers.com/clip/43740259/free_press_turns_grid_spotlight/|archive-date=February 6, 2020|type=clipping}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=Michigan Steamroller Pulverizes Pitt, 69 to 0|newspaper=[[Milwaukee Journal Sentinel|The Milwaukee Journal]]|date=October 12, 1947|url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?id=8ywaAAAAIBAJ&sjid=AiUEAAAAIBAJ&pg=2817,5784194&dq=bob-mann&hl=en|access-date=November 21, 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181004145950/https://news.google.com/newspapers?id=8ywaAAAAIBAJ&sjid=AiUEAAAAIBAJ&pg=2817,5784194&dq=bob-mann&hl=en|archive-date=October 4, 2018|url-status=live|via=[[Google News Archive]]}}</ref>\n\nAfter the 1947 season, Mann and fellow Michigan end, [[Len Ford]], played in the [[East\u2013West Shrine Bowl|East-West college all-star game]] at [[Gilmore Stadium]] in [[Los Angeles]]; both caught touchdown passes in the game.<ref>{{cite news|last=Hyland|first=Dick|url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/39377791/3083_see_west_grids_top_east/|title=3083 See West Grids Top East|newspaper=[[Los Angeles Times]]|date=January 19, 1948|url-status=live|via=[[Newspapers.com]]|type=clipping|page=9|access-date=November 21, 2019|archive-date=November 21, 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191121161339/https://www.newspapers.com/clip/39377791/3083_see_west_grids_top_east/}}</ref> Mann was also selected by the [[Associated Press]] as a first-team end for its All-Big Nine team.<ref>{{cite news|title=Chappuis, Elliott, Yerges, Mann Named on First Team of All-Big Nine Gridders|newspaper=[[The Michigan Daily]]|date=November 25, 1947|page=3|url=https://digital.bentley.umich.edu/midaily/mdp.39015071756220/365|access-date=February 6, 2020|via=[[Bentley Historical Library]]|url-status=live|agency=[[Associated Press]]|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200206213752/https://digital.bentley.umich.edu/midaily/mdp.39015071756220/365|archive-date=February 6, 2020}}</ref> He was also selected as a second-team [[1947 College Football All-America Team|All-American]] by the Associated Press and the [[Football Writers Association of America]], and Michigan coach Crisler called him \"the greatest pass receiver he has ever coached\".<ref>{{cite news|title=A-A Polls Bypass 'M' Specialists|newspaper=[[The Michigan Daily]]|last=Widenthal|first=Bud|date=January 1, 1948|page=4|url-status=live|access-date=February 6, 2020|url=https://digital.bentley.umich.edu/midaily/mdp.39015071756220/508|via=[[Bentley Historical Library]]|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200206213600/https://digital.bentley.umich.edu/midaily/mdp.39015071756220/508|archive-date=February 6, 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Professional football==\n\n===Detroit Lions===\nIn February 1948, Mann traveled to New York and met with [[New York Yankees (AAFC)|New York Yankees]] coach [[Ray Flaherty]]. Mann said at the time that he would like to play for the Yankees, but was reluctant to agree to any terms as he was expecting to receive feelers from several other teams in the [[All-America Football Conference]] (AAFC) and [[National Football League]] (NFL).<ref>{{cite news|title=Bob Mann, Ford Weigh Pro Football Careers|newspaper=[[Baltimore Afro-American|The Afro American]]|date=February 7, 1948|url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?id=zNMmAAAAIBAJ&sjid=fAIGAAAAIBAJ&pg=4029,862098&dq=bob-mann+football&hl=en|access-date=November 21, 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181004145950/https://news.google.com/newspapers?id=zNMmAAAAIBAJ&sjid=fAIGAAAAIBAJ&pg=4029,862098&dq=bob-mann+football&hl=en|archive-date=October 4, 2018|url-status=live|via=[[Google News Archives]]}}</ref> In April 1948, Mann signed with the [[Detroit Lions]] of the NFL;<ref>{{Cite news | title = Mann signs with Lions| date = April 21, 1948| access-date = November 22, 2019| newspaper = [[Detroit Free Press]]| page = 20| url = https://www.newspapers.com/clip/21069682/mann_signs_with_lions/| archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20191122154650/https://www.newspapers.com/clip/21069682/mann_signs_with_lions/| archive-date = November 22, 2019| url-status=live | via = [[Newspapers.com]]|type=clipping}}</ref> his first NFL contract was for $7,500.<ref name=\"EMBODY\"/> He was also hired to a sales position at the [[Goebel Brewing Company]], which was owned by Lions' president Edwin J. Anderson.<ref name=\"PIONEER\"/> At the time, Detroit's new head coach [[Bo McMillin]]<ref>{{Cite news | url = https://www.newspapers.com/clip/39431950/mmillin_signs_as_new_coach_of_pro/ | via = [[Newspapers.com]]|type=clipping | df = mdy | url-status = live | newspaper = [[South Bend Tribune]] | agency = [[Associated Press]] | page = 1 | title = M'Millin Signs as New Coach of Pro Eleven | date = February 19, 1948 | access-date = November 22, 2019 | archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20191122162255/https://www.newspapers.com/clip/39431950/mmillin_signs_as_new_coach_of_pro/| archive-date = November 22, 2019}}</ref> said, \"We're tickled to get Mann. We've been after his name on a Detroit contract ever since I came here as a coach. We know he will be a valuable professional performer\".<ref name=Signs>{{cite news|title=Detroit Lions Sign Bob Mann|newspaper=[[Tampa Bay Times|St. Petersburg Times]]|date=April 23, 1948|url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?id=7BgLAAAAIBAJ&sjid=Fk8DAAAAIBAJ&pg=5716,800272&dq=bob-mann&hl=en|access-date=November 21, 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181004145950/https://news.google.com/newspapers?id=7BgLAAAAIBAJ&sjid=Fk8DAAAAIBAJ&pg=5716,800272&dq=bob-mann&hl=en|archive-date=October 4, 2018|url-status=live|via=[[Google News Archive]]}}</ref>\n\n====1948 season====\n[[File:BobMann1948Bowman.jpg|thumb|right|Mann's 1948 [[Bowman Gum|Bowman]] football card|alt=A black and white photo of Mann posing catching a football with one hand]]\nAs a rookie in 1948, Mann became the first African American to play for the Lions; halfback [[Mel Groomes]] also played for the Lions in 1948.<ref name=\"FIRST\"/> Although team owners denied the existence of a ban, no African American had played in the NFL between 1933 and 1945.<ref name=\"PIONEER1\">{{Cite news | first = Bill| last = Dow| title = Mann pioneer player in NFL: Part 1| date = January 11, 2002| access-date = November 22, 2019| url-status=live | newspaper = [[Detroit Free Press]]| page = 1D| url = https://www.newspapers.com/clip/24262923/mann_pioneer_player_in_nfl/| archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20191122153444/https://www.newspapers.com/clip/24262923/mann_pioneer_player_in_nfl/| archive-date = November 22, 2019| via = [[Newspapers.com]]|type=clipping}}</ref> Teams in the rival AAFC were much more willing to sign African American players. Even after African American players began appearing in NFL playing rosters, it took many years for them to be given the same opportunities as white players.{{sfn|Piascik|2007|p=190}}\n\nMann appeared in all 12 games for the Lions, though none as a starter. Despite his role as a backup, Mann finished the season with 33 catches for 560 yards, ranking him seventh in the NFL in receiving yards and fourth in yards per reception.<ref name=PFR>{{cite web|title=Bob Mann profile|publisher=Sports Reference LLC.|url=https://www.pro-football-reference.com/players/M/MannBo00.htm|access-date=November 21, 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100913051639/http://www.pro-football-reference.com/players/M/MannBo00.htm|archive-date=September 13, 2010|url-status=live}}</ref> In December 1948, Mann joined [[Jesse Owens]]' Olympians professional basketball team in Cleveland. He had played two years of college basketball at Hampton Institute.<ref>{{cite news|title=Bob Mann Joins Owens' Professional Cage Team|url = https://www.newspapers.com/clip/40167617/bob_mann_joins_owens_professional_cage/ | agency = [[Associated Press]] | newspaper=[[Lansing State Journal]]|date=December 19, 1948|url-status=live|archive-date=December 6, 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191206173730/https://www.newspapers.com/clip/40167617/bob_mann_joins_owens_professional_cage/|access-date=December 6, 2019|via=[[Newspapers.com]]|page=3|type=clipping}}</ref>\n\n====1949 season====\nIn the preseason before the [[1949 NFL season]], the Lions played an [[exhibition game]] against the [[Philadelphia Eagles]] in [[New Orleans]]. Coach McMillin met with the Lions' African American players, including Mann, and explained that due to racial issues, they would not be able to play in the game.<ref name=\"PIONEER\"/> McMillin thought it would be best for everyone to not incite any further racial issues in the city.<ref name=\"EMBODY\"/>\n\nOn December 11, 1949, Mann was credited with eight catches for 182 yards and two touchdowns (including a 64-yard touchdown pass from [[Frank Tripucka]] in the first quarter and a 41-yard touchdown pass in the fourth quarter) against the [[Green Bay Packers]].<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/39346487/packers_end_season_with_21_to_7_loss/|title=Packers End Season With 21 To 7 Loss|newspaper=[[The Sheboygan Press]]|agency=[[Associated Press]]|date=December 12, 1949|page=19|url-status=live|access-date=November 21, 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191120225722/https://www.newspapers.com/clip/39346487/packers_end_season_with_21_to_7_loss/|archive-date=November 20, 2019|via=[[Newspapers.com]]|type=clipping}}</ref> After the game, Mann's wife, described as \"an ardent football fan,\" told statistician Nick Kerbawy that her tally sheet showed that her husband caught nine passes. Kerbawy reexamined the play-by-play account and discovered she was right.<ref>{{Cite news | url = https://www.newspapers.com/clip/40168232/manns_wife_gets_assist/ | title = Mann's Wife Gets Assist | agency = [[United Press International|United Press]] | newspaper = [[Akron Beacon Journal]] | date = December 19, 1949 | url-status = live | page = 27 | access-date = December 6, 2019 | archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20191206175209/https://www.newspapers.com/clip/40168232/manns_wife_gets_assist/ | archive-date = December 6, 2019 | type = clipping | via = [[Newspapers.com]]}}</ref> The new total of nine receptions set a new Lions' record for a single game.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/39399931/mrs_bob_mann_on_the_job_hubby_sets/|title=Mrs. Bob Mann On The Job, Hubby Sets New Record|via=[[Newspapers.com]]|type=clipping|newspaper=[[The Times Herald]]|date=December 14, 1949|page=16|url-status=live|agency=[[Associated Press]]|archive-date=November 21, 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191121224848/https://www.newspapers.com/clip/39399931/mrs_bob_mann_on_the_job_hubby_sets/}}</ref>\n\nDuring the 1949 season, Mann led the NFL with 1,014 receiving yards and 15.4 yards per catch.<ref name=LAT/> He also finished second in receptions with 66 ([[Tom Fears]] set an NFL record in 1949 with 77 receptions).<ref name=LAT/><ref>{{cite news|title=Rams' Fears Tops NFL Pass Catchers|agency=[[Associated Press]]|url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/39375659/rams_fears_tops_nfl_pass_catchers/|via=[[Newspapers.com]]|type=clipping|newspaper=[[Los Angeles Times]]|date=February 23, 1950|access-date=November 21, 2019|page=2|url-status=live|archive-date=November 21, 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191121151757/https://www.newspapers.com/clip/39375659/rams_fears_tops_nfl_pass_catchers/}}</ref> At the time, Mann's season totals in receiving yards and receptions both ranked in the top five all-time.<ref>{{Cite web | url = https://www.pro-football-reference.com/leaders/rec_single_season_1949.htm | title = NFL Single-Season Reception Leaders Through 1949 | publisher = Sports Reference LLC | access-date = December 6, 2019 | url-status = live | archive-date = December 6, 2019| archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20191206172325/https://www.pro-football-reference.com/leaders/rec_single_season_1949.htm}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web | url = https://www.pro-football-reference.com/leaders/rec_yds_single_season_1949.htm | title = NFL Single-Season Receiving Yards Leaders Through 1949 | publisher = Sports Reference LLC | access-date = December 6, 2019 | url-status = live | archive-date = December 6, 2019| archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20191206172504/https://www.pro-football-reference.com/leaders/rec_yds_single_season_1949.htm}}</ref> He also became the first Lions' player to eclipse 1,000 receiving yards in a season.<ref name=\"FIRST\">{{Cite news | url = https://www.latimes.com/archives/la-xpm-2006-oct-25-me-passings25.1-story.html | title = Bob Mann, 82; Detroit Lions\u2019 receiver later became a lawyer | date = October 25, 2006 | access-date = November 22, 2019 | newspaper = [[Los Angeles Times]] | df = mdy | url-status = live | archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20191203203737/https://www.latimes.com/archives/la-xpm-2006-oct-25-me-passings25.1-story.html| archive-date = December 3, 2019}}</ref> Despite leading the NFL in receiving yards, Mann was not selected by the [[United Press International|United Press]] (UP) for either its first- or second-team All-NFL team. Instead, he was named in its \"Honorable Mention\" team.<ref>{{cite news|title=Four Rams Selected on All-NFL Team|newspaper=[[Los Angeles Times]]|url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/39375492/four_rams_selected_on_allnfl_team/|page=1|access-date=November 21, 2019|url-status=live|via=[[Newspapers.com]]|type=clipping|date=December 13, 1949|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191121151312/https://www.newspapers.com/clip/39375492/four_rams_selected_on_allnfl_team/|archive-date=November 21, 2019}}</ref>\n\n====Salary dispute====\nDuring the off-season in 1950, the Lions asked Mann to take a $1,500 pay cut from $7,500 to $6,000.<ref name=LAT/> According to the Lions, the pay cut request was based off of the larger number of available players and the merger of the AAFC and NFL before the start of the season.{{sfn|Ross|2001|p=123-124}} Mann objected and held out, refusing to sign a 1950 contract.<ref>{{cite news|title=Lions Send Mann to Grid Yankees|url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/39384297/lions_send_mann_to_grid_yankees/|via=[[Newspapers.com]]|newspaper=[[The Scranton Times-Tribune|Scrantonian Tribune]]|agency=[[United Press International|United Press]]|date=August 6, 1950|url-status=live|page=37|archive-date=November 21, 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191121182119/https://www.newspapers.com/clip/39384297/lions_send_mann_to_grid_yankees/}}</ref> Further complicating the negotiations, the African American community in Detroit had called for a boycott of Goebel beer, after a bid by an African American group for a distributorship in Detroit's black community had been rejected.{{sfn|Ross|2001|p=123-124}} Mann recalled that Goebels/Lions president Anderson was under the mistaken impression that Mann had met with representatives of the boycott.{{sfn|Piascik|2009|p=31}}{{sfn|Ross|2001|p=123}}\n\n===New York Yankees===\nOn July 31, 1950, Mann became a hold out when he failed to show up on the first day of practice for the Lions.<ref>{{Cite news | url = https://www.newspapers.com/clip/40179021/lions_start_grid_drills/ | title = Lions Start Grid Drills | via = [[Newspapers.com]] | url-status= live | type = clipping | newspaper = [[Lansing State Journal]] | page = 11 | access-date = December 6, 2019 | archive-date = December 6, 2019 | archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20191206212706/https://www.newspapers.com/clip/40179021/lions_start_grid_drills/}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news | url = https://www.newspapers.com/clip/21091473/mann_traded_to_yankees/ | title = Lions Toss In Bob Mann on Layne Deal | date = August 5, 1950 | newspaper = [[Detroit Free Press]] | url-status = live | access-date = December 6, 2019 | page = 12 | via = [[Newspapers.com]] | type = clipping | archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20191206212337/https://www.newspapers.com/clip/21091473/mann_traded_to_yankees/ | archive-date = December 6, 2019}}</ref> That same day, his position for Goebel was terminated.{{sfn|Ross|2001|p=123-124}} Four days later, he was sent to the Yankees in payment for quarterback [[Bobby Layne]].<ref>{{cite news|title=Lions Send Bob Mann to Yanks to Pay for Layne|url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/39376175/lions_send_bob_mann_to_yanks_to_pay_for/|newspaper=[[Chicago Tribune]]|agency=[[Associated Press]]|url-status=live|via=[[Newspapers.com]]|type=clipping|access-date=November 21, 2019|page=4|date=August 5, 1950|archive-date=November 21, 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191121153333/https://www.newspapers.com/clip/39376175/lions_send_bob_mann_to_yanks_to_pay_for/}}</ref> The Lions had previously traded fullback Camp Wilson for Layne, but Wilson refused to report to the Yankees.<ref name=Hold>{{cite news|title=Lions Send Bob Mann To Yanks for Layne|url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/39376341/lions_send_bob_mann_to_yanks_for_layne/|url-status=live|page=8|agency=[[United Press International|United Press]]|newspaper=[[Ironwood Daily Globe]]|date=August 5, 1950|via=[[Newspapers.com]]|type=clipping|archive-date=November 21, 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191121153648/https://www.newspapers.com/clip/39376341/lions_send_bob_mann_to_yanks_for_layne/}}</ref> Mann later recalled that Yankees' coach [[Red Strader]] was upset about the trade. Despite a good training camp, Mann received little playing time in exhibition games. [[John Rauch]], a rookie quarterback, told Mann that he had been ordered not to throw to him. The day after Rauch threw a 50-yard touchdown pass to Mann in a pre-season game against the [[Washington Redskins]], Mann was released by the Yankees.<ref name=\"BLOCKING\"/> He was not picked up by any other team and officially became a free agent.{{sfn|Freedman|2013|p=71}}\n\n====Charges of blackballing====\nThrough the months of September and October 1950, Mann was jobless. At the end of October 1950, Mann publicly charged that he had been \"railroaded\" out of professional football. He claimed that, despite leading the NFL in receiving yards in 1949, the Lions had asked him to take a 20 percent pay cut. After he objected, he contended that the NFL had taken a \"hands off\" policy toward him. Mann publicly stated, \"I must have been blackballed -- it just doesn't make sense that I'm suddenly not good enough to make a single team in the league\".<ref name=LAT>{{cite news|title=Bob Mann Aims Charge that He Was 'Railroaded' at NFL|newspaper=[[Los Angeles Times]]|agency=[[United Press International|United Press]]|date=November 1, 1950|url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/39385357/bob_mann_aims_charge_that_he_was/|via=[[Newspapers.com]]|type=clipping|page=3|access-date=November 21, 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191121184221/https://www.newspapers.com/clip/39385357/bob_mann_aims_charge_that_he_was/|archive-date=November 21, 2019}}</ref> The Lions' response to Mann's charge was a statement that they felt he was too small in stature to be an effective blocker.<ref name=\"BLOCKING\">{{Cite news | url = https://www.newspapers.com/clip/21071367/mann_says_he_was_railroaded/ | type = clipping | title = 'Railroaded' Says Bob Mann | newspaper = [[The Times Herald]] | date = October 31, 1950 | last = Le Donne | first = Jerry | access-date = December 6, 2019 | page = 18 | agency = [[United Press International|United Press]] | via = [[Newspapers.com]] | url-status = live | archive-date = December 6, 2019 | archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20191206171338/https://www.newspapers.com/clip/21071367/mann_says_he_was_railroaded/}}</ref> Mann filed a lawsuit against the NFL based on his belief that NFL owners colluded to avoid signing him. Commissioner [[Bert Bell]] disagreed, even though he was familiar with the way that team owners had colluded to avoid signing black players over the previous decade.{{sfn|Piascik|2009|p=33}}\n\n===Green Bay Packers===\n[[File:Len Ford and Bob Mann (1947).png|thumb|right|Mann (right) with Michigan teammate and future hall of famer [[Len Ford]] (left) in 1947. Both Mann and Ford later played for the Packers, although not at the same time.|alt=Bob Mann and Len Ford wearing suits standing next to each other]]\n\n====1950&ndash;1951====\nMann was signed by the Green Bay Packers on November 25, 1950, ending his suit against the NFL.{{sfn|Piascik|2009|p=33}}<ref>{{cite news|title=Green Bay Packers Sign End Bob Mann|newspaper=[[Wisconsin State Journal]]|url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/39376055/green_bay_packers_sign_end_bob_mann/|agency=[[Associated Press]]|url-status=live|access-date=November 21, 2019|via=[[Newspapers.com]]|type=clipping|date=November 26, 1950|archive-date=November 21, 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191121152917/https://www.newspapers.com/clip/39376055/green_bay_packers_sign_end_bob_mann/|page=3}}</ref> On November 26, 1950, he appeared in the Packers' final home game against the [[San Francisco 49ers]], becoming the first African-American to play for the team.<ref name=\"PACK\"/><ref name=MCT>{{cite news|url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/39346733/first_black_packer_dies/|via=[[Newspapers.com]]|type=clipping|url-status=live|title=First Black Packer Dies|newspaper=[[The Capital Times]]|date=October 24, 2006|page=D2|access-date=November 21, 2019|archive-date=November 20, 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191120230147/https://www.newspapers.com/clip/39346733/first_black_packer_dies/}}</ref> It was later determined that [[Walt Jean]], an [[offensive lineman]] for the Packers in the 1920s, was African American through his father's side of the family. However, this knowledge was not known by Jean's teammates at the time, thus the color barrier was officially broken for the Packers when Mann played his first game with the team.<ref name=\"PACK\"/> Mann ended up playing in three games for the Packers in 1950, catching six passes for 89 yards and one touchdown.<ref name=PFR/>\n\nIn 1951, Mann led the Packers with 50 catches, 696 receiving yards, and eight touchdowns;{{sfn|Freedman|2013|p=91}} he also ranked fourth in the NFL in both receptions and receiving yards that year.<ref name=PFR/><ref name=MCT/> Mann's best performance in 1951 came in an October game against the Philadelphia Eagles; he caught three touchdown passes while the Packers upset the favored Eagles.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/39382852/green_bay_aerial_circus_upsets_eagles/|title=Green Bay Aerial Circus Upsets Eagles, 37&ndash;24|newspaper=[[La Crosse Tribune]]|date=October 15, 1951|agency=[[Associated Press]]|access-date=November 21, 2019|url-status=live|via=[[Newspapers.com]]|type=clipping|page=11|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191121175443/https://www.newspapers.com/clip/39382852/green_bay_aerial_circus_upsets_eagles/|archive-date=November 21, 2019}}</ref> The Packers ended the season with a record of 3&ndash;9, the fourth straight season they won three or less games.<ref>{{Cite web | url = https://www.pro-football-reference.com/teams/gnb/index.htm | url-status = live | title = Green Bay Packers Team Encyclopedia | access-date = December 11, 2019 | publisher = Sports Reference LLC | archive-date = March 24, 2019 | archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20190324190901/https://www.pro-football-reference.com/teams/gnb/index.htm}}</ref>\n\n====1952&ndash;1955====\nIn the [[1952 NFL draft]], the Packers selected [[Rice University]] end [[Billy Howton]] with their second round pick.<ref>{{Cite new | url = https://www.newspapers.com/clip/40380139/five_all_america_stars_top_packer_draft/ | url-status = live | type = clipping | via = [[Newspapers.com]] | title = Five All America Stars Top Packer Draft Picks | last = Daley | first = Art | date = January 18, 1952 | access-date = December 10, 2019 | page = 9 | newspaper = [[Green Bay Press-Gazette]] | archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20191210202750/https://www.newspapers.com/clip/40380139/five_all_america_stars_top_packer_draft/| archive-date = December 10, 2019}}</ref> Howton, who elicited comparisons to Hall of Famer [[Don Hutson]], made an immediate impact on the Packers, leading the league in 1952 with 1,231 receiving yards.<ref>{{Cite news | url = https://www.newspapers.com/clip/40381216/packers_hail_howton_as_new_don_hutson/ | title = Packers Hail Howton As New Don Hutson | newspaper = [[The Terre Haute Tribune]] | date = December 16, 1952 | access-date = December 10, 2019 | url-status = live | type = clipping | via = [[Newspapers.com]] | page = 12 | archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20191210204627/https://www.newspapers.com/clip/40381216/packers_hail_howton_as_new_don_hutson/ | archive-date = December 10, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web | url = https://www.pro-football-reference.com/years/1952/receiving.htm | title = 1952 NFL Receiving | access-date = December 10, 2019 | publisher = Sports Reference LLC | url-status = live | archive-date = December 10, 2019 | archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20190702131316/https://www.pro-football-reference.com/years/1952/receiving.htm}}</ref> Even with Howton in the lineup, Mann had a productive year, recording 30 receptions for 517 yards and six touchdowns.<ref name=PFR/> The Packers improved their record to 6&ndash;6, finishing fourth in [[Eastern and Western Conferences (NFL) 1933\u201369|their conference]].<ref>{{Cite web | url = https://www.pro-football-reference.com/years/1952/index.htm | title = 1952 NFL Standings & Team Stats | publisher = Sports Reference LLC | access-date = December 11, 2019 | url-status = live | archive-date = July 26, 2019 | archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20190726133340/https://www.pro-football-reference.com/years/1952/index.htm}}</ref>\n\nBy 1953, Mann and Howton were considered one of the best receiving duos in the league, though both players missed numerous games due to injury throughout the season.<ref>{{Cite news | url = https://www.newspapers.com/clip/40417742/packers_ace_pass_catchers_reunited/ | newspaper = [[Green Bay Press-Gazette]] | via = [[Newspapers.com]] | title = Packers' Ace Pass Catchers Reunited | date = November 11, 1953 | access-date = December 11, 2019 | url-status = live | type = clipping | last = Daley | first = Art | page = 21 | archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20191211162610/https://www.newspapers.com/clip/40417742/packers_ace_pass_catchers_reunited/ | archive-date = December 11, 2019}}</ref> In ten games, Mann finished the year with 23 receptions for 327 yards and two touchdowns, all of which were second to Howton's totals for the season.<ref>{{Cite web | url = https://web.archive.org/web/20190417230219/https://www.pro-football-reference.com/teams/gnb/1953.htm | title = 1953 Green Bay Packers Statistics & Players | publisher = Sports Reference LLC | access-date = December 11, 2019 | url-status = live | archive-date = April 17, 2019| archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20190417230219/https://www.pro-football-reference.com/teams/gnb/1953.htm}}</ref> Mann's best game in 1953 came in a 21&ndash;21 tie against the [[1953 Chicago Bears season|Chicago Bears]]; according to the ''[[Green Bay Press-Gazette]]'', Mann \"was open all afternoon as the Bears chased Howton\" while catching six passes for 101 yards, including a 45-yard catch.<ref>{{Cite news | url = https://www.newspapers.com/clip/40418669/packers_gain_tie_with_bears_in_last/ | newspaper = [[Green Bay Press-Gazette]] | via = [[Newspapers.com]] | title = Packers Gain Tie With Bears in Last Minute 21&ndash;21 | date = November 9, 1953 | access-date = December 11, 2019 | url-status = live | type = clipping | last = Daley | first = Art | page = 19 | archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20191211165006/https://www.newspapers.com/clip/40418669/packers_gain_tie_with_bears_in_last/ | archive-date = December 11, 2019}}</ref> The Packers ended the year in last place in their conference with a record of 2&ndash;9&ndash;1.<ref>{{cite web | url = https://www.pro-football-reference.com/years/1953/index.htm  | title = 1953 NFL Standings & Team Stats | publisher = Sports Reference LLC | access-date = December 11, 2019 | url-status = live | archive-date = August 19, 2019 | archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20190819053706/https://www.pro-football-reference.com/years/1953/index.htm}}</ref>\n\nIn 1954, Mann played in only two of the Packers' first four games.<ref name=\"PACK\"/> In those two games, he did not record a catch.<ref name=PFR/> He had sustained a knee injury during a preseason game against the [[1954 Philadelphia Eagles season|Philadelphia Eagles]] and was subsequently released by the team six weeks later in October.<ref name=\"PACK\"/> In November 1955, Mann filed a $25,000 breach of contract suit against the Packers. Mann claimed his release was illegal because he was not given written notice by the team.<ref>{{cite news|title=Mann Files $25,000 Suit Against Packers|url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/39375914/mann_files_25000_suit_against_packers/|page=24|via=[[Newspapers.com]]|type=clipping|url-status=live|agency=[[Associated Press]]|newspaper=[[Ironwood Daily Globe]]|date=November 24, 1955|access-date=November 21, 2019|archive-date=November 21, 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191121152534/https://www.newspapers.com/clip/39375914/mann_files_25000_suit_against_packers/}}</ref><ref name=\"ILLEGAL\">{{cite news|title=Suit Filed by Packers' Mann Goes to Detroit|url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/39375801/suit_filed_by_packers_mann_goes_to/|url-status=live|access-date=November 21, 2019|newspaper=[[Chicago Tribune]]|page=4|agency=[[Associated Press]]|via=[[Newspapers.com]]|type=clipping|date=January 5, 1956|archive-date=November 21, 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191121152239/https://www.newspapers.com/clip/39375801/suit_filed_by_packers_mann_goes_to/}}</ref> Mann and the Packers ultimately settled the lawsuit for an undisclosed amount in 1957.<ref>{{Cite web | url = https://books.google.com/books?id=oYZS-PVuqdQC&lpg=PA2827&ots=tyVm4D0qZA&dq=bob%20mann%20packers%20lawsuit&pg=PA2827#v=onepage&q=bob%20mann%20packers%20lawsuit&f=false | via = [[Google Books]] | date = June\u2013August 1957 | title = Hearings Before the Antitrust Subcommittee of the Committee on the Judiciary House of Representatives | publisher = [[United States Congress]] | df = mdy | url-status = live | archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20191126195558/https://books.google.com/books?id=oYZS-PVuqdQC&pg=PA2827&lpg=PA2827&dq=bob+mann+packers+lawsuit&source=bl&ots=tyVm4D0qZA&sig=ACfU3U0-cCrKv7dQEKmGQza7FLnCN_efVw&hl=en&sa=X&ved=2ahUKEwiXzLmS0YjmAhVjFzQIHfpABYYQ6AEwA3oECAkQAQ#v=onepage&q=bob%20mann%20packers%20lawsuit&f=false | archive-date = November 26, 2019 | access-date = November 26, 2019}}</ref> Mann's knee injury forced him to retire from professional football.{{sfn|Gulbrandsen|2007|p=62}}\n\n====Race====\nWhen Mann joined the Packers, the city of [[Green Bay, Wisconsin]] had fewer than 20 black residents. Even with this lack of racial diversity, Mann's time with the Packers was largely free of overt racial incidents.{{sfn|Maxymuk|2003|p=352}} However, racial issues often arose when Mann traveled to other cities with the team.{{sfn|Freedman|2013|p=71}} ''[[Green Bay Gazette]]'' sports writer Art Daley recalled a story involving Mann and teammate [[Dick the Bruiser|Dick Afflis]], who later became known in professional wrestling as \"Dick the Bruiser\". The Packers stayed at a Baltimore hotel that would not allow Mann to stay with the team on account of its policy prohibiting African-American guests. When Mann left to go to another hotel, the {{Convert|252|lb|adj=on}} Afflis left with him. When a cab driver told Afflis that he would not drive Mann because of his race, Afflis grabbed the driver by the shirt and said, \"You will take him wherever he wants to go\".<ref name=NB/> Multiple white teammates reached out to Mann to welcome him after he signed with the Packers and coach [[Gene Ronzani]] gave him additional travel privileges to Milwaukee and Chicago.{{sfn|Maxymuk|2003|p=352}} Overall, Mann enjoyed his time in Green Bay, saying \"I never had any problems. Everyone treated me well\".<ref name=\"VANDER\"/>\n\n====Legacy====\nMann compiled 109 catches for 1,629 yards and 17 touchdowns over his five seasons with the Packers.{{sfn|Maxymuk|2003|p=352}} He was inducted into the [[Green Bay Packers Hall of Fame]] in 1988 in recognition of his contributions to the team.<ref name=GBHOF>{{cite news | title = Packers' first black downplays role | newspaper = [[Green Bay Press-Gazette]] | last = Egle | first = Jim | date = February 13, 1988 | page = 1C | type = clipping | url = https://www.newspapers.com/clip/43750014/packers_first_black_downplays_role/ | via = [[Newspapers.com]] | url-status = live | archive-date = February 7, 2020 | archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20200207001114/https://www.newspapers.com/clip/43750014/packers_first_black_downplays_role/}}</ref> His impact was largely felt off the field though, with the ''[[Detroit Free Press]]'' writing that Mann was a \"pioneer\" wherever he played football, breaking multiple color barriers and doing so in a \"dignified and friendly manner\" that showed his \"strength and determination\".<ref name=\"PIONEER\"/> Packers' team historian Cliff Christl noted that \"Mann endured unimaginable obstacles just to gain [the] opportunity\" to play professional football.<ref name=\"PACK\"/>\n\n==Legal career and personal life==\nAfter retiring from football, Mann returned to [[Detroit]] where he worked in real estate sales for the next decade.<ref name=PIONEER/><ref name=GBHOF/> He married in 1956, and with his wife, Vera, had two daughters, Marjorie and Marilyn.  In 1966, at age 43, Mann enrolled in night school at [[Detroit College of Law]].<ref name=PIONEER/><ref name=GBHOF/> He graduated from law school in 1970 and worked as a criminal defense lawyer for over 30 years in Detroit, heading the firm of Robert Mann & Associates.<ref name=PIONEER/><ref name=\"DEAD82\">{{Cite news | title = Ex-Lion, U-M receiver Mann, 82| date = October 25, 2006| access-date = November 22, 2019| url-status=live | newspaper = [[Detroit Free Press]]| page = 2E| url = https://www.newspapers.com/clip/24262849/exlion_um_receiver_mann_82/| archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20191122153333/https://www.newspapers.com/clip/24262849/exlion_um_receiver_mann_82/| archive-date = November 22, 2019| via = [[Newspapers.com]]|type=clipping}}</ref> Mann's law office was located a few blocks from the Detroit Lions' [[Ford Field]].<ref name=\"VANDER\">{{Cite news | last = Vandermause|first = Mike|title=Remembering Bob Mann: 1924-2006|newspaper=[[Green Bay Press-Gazette]]|date=October 24, 2006|page=C-2|url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/24266160/remembering_bob_mann/|via=[[Newspapers.com]]|type=clipping|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191122202346/https://www.newspapers.com/clip/24266160/remembering_bob_mann/|archive-date=November 22, 2019|access-date=November 22, 2019 | url-status=live}}</ref> At the Lions' first regular season game at Ford Field on September 22, 2002, Mann was the Lions' honorary captain.<ref name=NB/> Mann died in October 2006 at age 82, survived by his wife and two daughters.<ref name=\"DEAD82\"/>\n\n==References==\n===Sources===\n{{Reflist}}\n===Bibliography===\n{{Refbegin}}\n*{{cite book|last=Freedman|first=Lew|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=T030AwAAQBAJ&newbks=1&newbks_redir=0&lpg=PA1&dq=The%20Packers%20Experience%3A%20A%20Year-by-Year%20Chronicle%20of%20the%20Green%20Bay%20Packers&pg=PA71#v=onepage&q=Bob%20Mann&f=false|via=[[Google Books]]|title=The Packers Experience: A Year-by-Year Chronicle of the Green Bay Packers|publisher=[[MVP Books]]|location=[[Minneapolis, Minnesota|Minneapolis, MN]]|year=2013|isbn=978-0760344507|pages=240|ref=harv}}\n*{{cite book|last=Gulbrandsen|first=Don|title=Green Bay Packers: The Complete Illustrated History|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=PpXQ19EQMzcC&newbks=1&newbks_redir=0&lpg=PP1&dq=Green%20Bay%20Packers%3A%20The%20Complete%20Illustrated%20History&pg=PA63#v=onepage&q=Bob%20Mann&f=false|via=[[Google Books]]|publisher=[[Voyageur Press]]|location=[[St. Paul, Minnesota|St. Paul, MN]]|year=2007|isbn=978-0760331392|pages=208|ref=harv}}\n*{{Cite book | title = Packers by the Numbers: Jersey Numbers and the Players who Wore Them | url = https://books.google.com/books?id=m9o2_k8zu4QC&newbks=1&newbks_redir=0&lpg=PP1&dq=Packers%20by%20the%20Numbers%3A%20Jersey%20Numbers%20and%20the%20Players%20who%20Wore%20Them&pg=PA351#v=onepage&q=Bob%20Mann&f=false| via = [[Google Books]] | last = Maxymuk | first = John | year = 2003 | publisher = Big Earth Publishing | pages = 452 | ref = harv | location = [[Boulder, Colorado|Boulder, CO]]|isbn=978-1879483903}}\n*{{cite book|last=Piascik|first=Andy|title=The Best Show in Football: The 1946\u20131955 Cleveland Browns\u2014Pro Football's Greatest Dynasty|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=UXKX316bzU4C&newbks=1&newbks_redir=0&lpg=PP1&dq=The%20Best%20Show%20in%20Football%3A%20The%201946%E2%80%931955%20Cleveland%20Browns%E2%80%94Pro%20Football's%20Greatest%20Dynasty&pg=PA190#v=onepage&q=Bob%20Mann&f=false|via=[[Google Books]]|publisher=[[Taylor Trade Publishing]]|location=[[Lanham, Maryland|Lanham, MA]]|year=2007|isbn=978-1589793606|pages=430|ref=harv}}\n*{{cite book|last=Piascik|first=Andy|title=Gridiron Gauntlet: The Story of the Men Who Integrated Pro Football, In Their Own Words|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=f8SvKb4Gr5YC&newbks=1&newbks_redir=0&lpg=PP1&dq=Gridiron%20Gauntlet%3A%20The%20Story%20of%20the%20Men%20Who%20Integrated%20Pro%20Football%2C%20In%20Their%20Own%20Words&pg=PA31#v=onepage&q=Bob%20Mann&f=false|via=[[Google Books]]|publisher=[[Taylor Trade Publishing]]|location=[[Lanham, Maryland|Lanham, MA]]|year=2009|isbn=978-1589796522|pages=258|ref=harv}}\n*{{cite book|last=Ross|first=Charles K.|title=Outside the Lines: African Americans and the Integration of the National Football League|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=56oUCgAAQBAJ&newbks=1&newbks_redir=0&lpg=PP1&dq=Outside%20the%20Lines%3A%20African%20Americans%20and%20the%20Integration%20of%20the%20National%20Football%20League&pg=PA123#v=onepage&q=Bob%20Mann&f=false|via=[[Google Books]]|publisher=[[New York University Press]]|location=[[New York City|New York, NY]]|year=2001|isbn=978-0814774960|pages=220|ref=harv}}\n{{Refend}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons category}}\n* {{Find a Grave|16317197}}\n\n{{Navboxes| list1 =\n{{1947 Michigan Wolverines football navbox}}\n{{Green Bay Packers HOF}}\n{{NFL receiving yardage leaders}}\n}}\n{{Authority control}}\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Mann, Bob}}\n[[Category:1924 births]]\n[[Category:2006 deaths]]\n[[Category:American football ends]]\n[[Category:Detroit Lions players]]\n[[Category:Green Bay Packers players]]\n[[Category:Michigan Wolverines football players]]\n[[Category:Detroit College of Law alumni]]\n[[Category:Lawyers from Detroit]]\n[[Category:Sportspeople from Detroit]]\n[[Category:Sportspeople from New Bern, North Carolina]]\n[[Category:Players of American football from North Carolina]]\n[[Category:African-American players of American football]]\n", "text_old": "{{good article}}\n{{short description|American football wide receiver}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=February 2020}}\n{{Infobox NFL biography\n| image               = 1950 Bowman Bob Mann Yankees.jpg\n| alt                 = A football card showing a portrait of Mann in his blue Yankees jersey\n| caption             = Mann's 1950 [[Bowman Gum|Bowman]] football card\n| number              = 31, 87\n| position            = [[End (gridiron football)|End]]\n| birth_date          = {{Birth date|1924|04|08|mf=y}}\n| birth_place         = [[New Bern, North Carolina]], US\n| death_date          = {{death date and age|2006|10|21|1924|04|8}}\n| death_place         = [[Detroit, Michigan]], US\n| height_ft           = 5\n| height_in           = 11\n| weight_lb           = 172\n| high_school         = {{Ubl|[[J.T. Barber School|J. T. Barber]]|(New Bern, North Carolina, US)}}\n| college             = [[Michigan Wolverines football|Michigan]]\n| undraftedyear       = 1948\n| pastteamsnote       = yes\n| pastteams           = \n* [[Detroit Lions]] ([[1948 NFL season|1948]]\u2013[[1949 NFL season|1949]])\n* [[New York Yankees (AAFC)|New York Yankees]] ([[1950 NFL season|1950]])*\n* [[Green Bay Packers]] ([[1950 NFL season|1950]]\u2013[[1954 NFL season|1954]])\n| highlights          = \n* [[List of NFL annual receiving yards leaders|NFL receiving yards leader]] (1949)\n* [[Green Bay Packers Hall of Fame]]\n* Second-team [[College Football All-America Team|All-American]] ([[1947 College Football All-America Team|1947]])\n* First-team All-[[Big Ten Conference|Big Nine]] ([[1947 All-Big Nine Conference football team|1947]])\n| statlabel1          = Receptions\n| statvalue1          = 208\n| statlabel2          = Receiving yards\n| statvalue2          = 3,203\n| statlabel3          = Receiving touchdowns\n| statvalue3          = 24\n| nfl                 = 2520072\n| pfr                 = MannBo00\n}}\n\n'''Robert Mann''' (April 8, 1924 \u2013 October 21, 2006) was an American [[American football|professional football]] player in the [[National Football League]] (NFL). A native of [[New Bern, North Carolina]], Mann played [[college football]] at [[Hampton University|Hampton Institute]] in 1942 and 1943 and at the [[University of Michigan]] in 1944, 1946 and 1947. Playing the [[End (American football)|end]] position, he broke the [[Big Ten Conference]] record for receiving yardage in 1946 and again in 1947. After going undrafted in the [[1948 NFL Draft]], Mann would sign his first professional football contract with the [[Detroit Lions]], where he played for two seasons. He would later player for the [[Green Bay Packers]] for parts of five seasons until 1954. Mann was the first African American player for both teams.\n\nMann led the NFL in receiving yardage (1,014 yards) and yards per reception (15.4) in 1949. Mann was asked to take a pay cut after the 1949 season and became a hold out when the Lions opened practice in July 1950. He was traded to the [[New York Yankees (AAFC)|New York Yankees]] in August 1950 and released three weeks later. Mann charged that he had been \"railroaded\" out of professional football for refusing to take a pay cut. He signed with the Green Bay Packers near the end of the [[1950 NFL season]] and was the team's leading receiver in 1951. He remained with the Packers through the 1954 season. After his football career, Mann became a lawyer and practiced law in [[Detroit]]. He was inducted into the [[Green Bay Packers Hall of Fame]] in 1988 and died in October 2006 at the age of 82.\n\n==Early years==\nBob Mann was born in [[New Bern, North Carolina|New Bern]], the county seat of [[Craven County, North Carolina]], in 1924.<ref name=NB>{{cite news |last=Bryant|first=Arabelle|title=New Bern's Mann established several sports firsts |newspaper=[[Sun Journal (New Bern, North Carolina)|Sun Journal]]|date=January 16, 2010 |access-date=November 21, 2019 |url=http://www.newbernsj.com/news/mann-59214-bern-new.html |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100119021815/http://www.newbernsj.com/news/mann-59214-bern-new.html |archive-date=January 19, 2010 }}</ref> At the time of his childhood, New Bern was a small town of about 10,000 and was still segregated.<ref name=\"PIONEER\">{{Cite news | first = Bill| last = Dow| title = Mann pioneer player in NFL: Part 2| date = January 11, 2002| access-date = November 22, 2019| url-status=live |newspaper = [[Detroit Free Press]]| page = 8D| url = https://www.newspapers.com/clip/24262964/mann_end_was_one_of_1st_black_lions/| archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20191122153540/https://www.newspapers.com/clip/24262964/mann_end_was_one_of_1st_black_lions/| archive-date = November 22, 2019| via = [[Newspapers.com]]|type=clipping}}</ref> His father, William Mann, was a physician, and his mother, Clara Mann, was a supervisor of Craven County elementary schools. Mann began his football career at West Street High School in New Bern.<ref name=NB/>\n\n==College football==\n\n===Hampton Institute===\nIn 1941, Mann enrolled at Hampton Institute (now known as [[Hampton University]]), a [[Historically black colleges and universities|historically black university]] located in [[Hampton, Virginia]]. He joined the school's [[college football|football]] team, and as a sophomore, he scored 45 of Hampton's 99 points while playing at the left end position. He scored three [[touchdown]]s in Hampton's final game against [[Virginia Union University|Virginia Union]].<ref>{{cite news|title=Bob Mann Scores 45 Points|newspaper=[[Baltimore Afro-American|The Afro American]]|date=December 8, 1942|url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?id=Op4lAAAAIBAJ&sjid=4_QFAAAAIBAJ&pg=2974,6027682&dq=bob-mann&hl=en|access-date=November 21, 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181004145950/https://news.google.com/newspapers?id=Op4lAAAAIBAJ&sjid=4_QFAAAAIBAJ&pg=2974,6027682&dq=bob-mann&hl=en|archive-date=October 4, 2018|url-status=live|via=[[Google News Archive]]|page=23}}</ref>\n\n===University of Michigan===\n[[File:Bob Mann (American football).jpg|thumb|right|Mann posing in the 1947 [[University of Michigan]] yearbook|alt=Mann in his football gear posing as if he is running]]\nMann transferred to Michigan in 1944, with his father hoping that he would attend the school's medical program.<ref name=\"PIONEER\"/> He joined the football team as a [[Walk-on (sports)|walk-on]] and ended up being one of only two [[African-American]] players ([[Gene Derricotte]] was the other) on the [[1944 Michigan Wolverines football team]].<ref name=\"EMBODY\">{{Cite news | first = Charlie| last = Vincent| title = Bob Mann Embodies Sport's Real Lessons| date = February 13, 1988| url-status=live |access-date = November 22, 2019| newspaper = [[Detroit Free Press]]| page = 1D | url = https://www.newspapers.com/clip/24262813/bob_mann_embodies_sports_real_lessons/| archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20191122153227/https://www.newspapers.com/clip/24262813/bob_mann_embodies_sports_real_lessons/| archive-date = November 22, 2019| via = [[Newspapers.com]]|type=clipping}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=1944 Michigan Football Roster |publisher=[[Bentley Historical Library]] |url=http://141.211.39.65/allroster/FMPro?-DB=allrost.fp5&-Format=fbresult.htm&-SortField=name&-SortOrder=Ascend&year=1944&-max=170&-Find |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100819230444/http://141.211.39.65/allroster/FMPro?-DB=allrost.fp5&-Format=fbresult.htm&-SortField=name&-SortOrder=Ascend&year=1944&-max=170&-Find |url-status=dead |archive-date=August 19, 2010 |access-date=November 21, 2019 }}</ref> Mann took a year off for military service, serving in the [[United States Navy|Navy]] during [[World War II]], although he was stationed in [[Staten Island]] and was not deployed overseas.<ref name=\"PIONEER\"/>{{sfn|Piascik|2009|p=38}} After his service, he returned to Michigan in 1946.<ref name=\"PACK\">{{Cite web | first = Cliff | last = Christl | url = https://www.packers.com/news/bob-mann-endured-for-his-opportunity | title = Bob Mann endured for his opportunity | date = September 27, 2018 | access-date = November 22, 2019 | publisher = [[Green Bay Packers, Inc.]] | archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20180927180007/https://www.packers.com/news/bob-mann-endured-for-his-opportunity| archive-date = September 27, 2018| url-status = live}}</ref> \n \nMann started two games at the left end for [[Fritz Crisler]]'s [[1946 Michigan Wolverines football team|1946 Michigan football team]].<ref>{{cite web|title=1946 Football Team|publisher=[[Bentley Historical Library]]|access-date=February 6, 2020|url=https://bentley.umich.edu/athdept/football/fbteam/1946fbt.htm|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190615193345/https://bentley.umich.edu/athdept/football/fbteam/1946fbt.htm|archive-date=June 15, 2019|url-status=live}}</ref> On November 16 against [[1946 Wisconsin Badgers football team|Wisconsin]], he caught three passes for 74 yards and two touchdowns and also gained 26 yards on two [[end-around]] runs.<ref>{{cite news|type=clipping|title=Mention Mann In Lineman Poll|newspaper=[[The Michigan Daily]]|date=November 21, 1946|page=3|url=https://digital.bentley.umich.edu/midaily/mdp.39015071756212/337|via=[[Newspapers.com]]|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200207030730/https://digital.bentley.umich.edu/midaily/mdp.39015071756212/337|archive-date=February 6, 2020}}</ref> And against [[1946 Ohio State Buckeyes football team|Ohio State]] the following week, he caught five passes for 101 yards and two touchdowns and added 33 yards on two end-around plays.<ref>{{cite news | title = Michigan Routs OSU But Misses Crown: Part 1 | newspaper = [[The Michigan Daily]] | first = Clark | last = Baker | date = November 24, 1946 | pages = 1 | url = https://digital.bentley.umich.edu/midaily/mdp.39015071756212/353 | via = [[Bentley Historical Library]] | url-status = live | archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20200206201839/https://digital.bentley.umich.edu/midaily/mdp.39015071756212/353 | archive-date = February 6, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite news | title = Michigan Routs OSU But Misses Crown: Part 2 | newspaper = [[The Michigan Daily]] | first = Clark | last = Baker | date = November 24, 1946 | pages = 6 | url = https://digital.bentley.umich.edu/midaily/mdp.39015071756212/358 | via = [[Bentley Historical Library]] | url-status = live | archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20200211194413/https://digital.bentley.umich.edu/midaily/mdp.39015071756212/358 | archive-date = February 11, 2020}}</ref> Despite seeing only limited action, his 1946 total of 13 receptions for 284 receiving yards set a new [[Big Ten Conference]] record.<ref>{{Cite news | last = Smith | first = Wilfrid | title = Colleges Have Greatest Year for Football: Part 1 | newspaper = [[Chicago Tribune]] | date = December 22, 1946| page = Part 2, Page 1 | url = https://www.newspapers.com/clip/44052058/colleges_have_greatest_year_for/ | via = [[Newspapers.com]] | url-status = live| archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20200211194008/https://www.newspapers.com/clip/44052058/colleges_have_greatest_year_for/ | archive-date = February 6, 2020 | type = clipping}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news | last = Smith | first = Wilfrid | title = Colleges Have Greatest Year for Football: Part 2 | newspaper = [[Chicago Tribune]] | date = December 22, 1946 | page = Part 2, Page 4 | url = https://www.newspapers.com/clip/43735264/colleges_have_greatest_year_for_football/ | via = [[Newspapers.com]] | url-status = live | archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20200207031749/https://www.newspapers.com/clip/43735264/colleges_have_greatest_year_for_football/ | archive-date = February 11, 2020 | type = clipping}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=Michigan Shifts Mann|newspaper=[[Chicago Tribune]]|page=36|date=September 19, 1947|url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/43735398/michigan_shifts_mann/|via=[[Newspapers.com]]|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200207030914/https://www.newspapers.com/clip/43735398/michigan_shifts_mann/|archive-date=February 6, 2020|url-status=live|type=clipping}}</ref> With 30 points on five touchdowns, Mann was also the second-leading scorer on the 1946 Michigan team, trailing only placekicker [[Jim Brieske]].<ref>{{cite news|title=Michigan Scoring Honors Copped by Two Linemen|newspaper=[[The Michigan Daily]]|first=Alys|last=George|date=November 27, 1946|page=3|url=https://digital.bentley.umich.edu/midaily/mdp.39015071756212/369|via=[[Bentley Historical Library]]|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200207031656/https://digital.bentley.umich.edu/midaily/mdp.39015071756212/369|archive-date=February 6, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> He also gained 114 yards on nine end-around plays in 1946, earning him a nickname as the \"fifth man\" in Michigan's backfield.<ref>{{cite news|title=Wolverines' '5th Back' Set for Spartan Opener|newspaper=[[Detroit Free Press]]|first=Tommy|last=Devine|date=September 25, 1947|page=23|url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/43738658/wolverines_5th_back_set_for_spartan/|via=[[Newspapers.com]]|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200207031012/https://www.newspapers.com/clip/43738658/wolverines_5th_back_set_for_spartan/|archive-date=February 6, 2020|url-status=live|type=clipping}}</ref>\n\nAs a senior, Mann started seven games at left end on Crisler's undefeated [[1947 Michigan Wolverines football team|1947 Michigan team]].<ref name=t47>{{cite web|title=1947 Football Team|publisher=[[Bentley Historical Library]]|url=http://bentley.umich.edu/athdept/football/fbteam/1947fbt.htm|access-date=November 21, 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110724041347/http://bentley.umich.edu/athdept/football/fbteam/1947fbt.htm|archive-date=July 24, 2011|url-status=live}}</ref> He caught 12 passes for 302 yards and three touchdowns and ran for 129 yards on 15 end-around plays.<ref name=Signs/> On October 4, against [[1947 Stanford Cardinal football team|Stanford]], Mann caught a 61-yard touchdown pass from [[Bob Chappuis]] on Michigan's second play of the game.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/39399188/wolverines_grind_out_4913_victory_over/|title=Wolverines Grind Out 49-13 Victory Over Stanford|newspaper=[[The Cincinnati Enquirer]]|page=42|url-status=live|date=October 5, 1947|via=[[Newspapers.com]]|type=clipping|agency=[[Associated Press]]|access-date=November 21, 2019|archive-date=November 21, 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191121223636/https://www.newspapers.com/clip/39399188/wolverines_grind_out_4913_victory_over/}}</ref> Against [[1947 Pittsburgh Panthers football team|Pitt]] the following week, he caught three passes for 105 yards and two touchdowns, including a 70-yard scoring play on a pass from Chappuis.<ref>{{cite news|title=Free Press Turns Grid Spotlight on U-M's Mann, Wistert, C. Elliott|newspaper=[[Detroit Free Press]]|first=Tommy|last=Devine|date=October 14, 1947|page=16|url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/43740259/free_press_turns_grid_spotlight/|via=[[Newspapers.com]]|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200207031202/https://www.newspapers.com/clip/43740259/free_press_turns_grid_spotlight/|archive-date=February 6, 2020|type=clipping}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=Michigan Steamroller Pulverizes Pitt, 69 to 0|newspaper=[[Milwaukee Journal Sentinel|The Milwaukee Journal]]|date=October 12, 1947|url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?id=8ywaAAAAIBAJ&sjid=AiUEAAAAIBAJ&pg=2817,5784194&dq=bob-mann&hl=en|access-date=November 21, 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181004145950/https://news.google.com/newspapers?id=8ywaAAAAIBAJ&sjid=AiUEAAAAIBAJ&pg=2817,5784194&dq=bob-mann&hl=en|archive-date=October 4, 2018|url-status=live|via=[[Google News Archive]]}}</ref>\n\nAfter the 1947 season, Mann and fellow Michigan end, [[Len Ford]], played in the [[East\u2013West Shrine Bowl|East-West college all-star game]] at [[Gilmore Stadium]] in [[Los Angeles]]; both caught touchdown passes in the game.<ref>{{cite news|last=Hyland|first=Dick|url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/39377791/3083_see_west_grids_top_east/|title=3083 See West Grids Top East|newspaper=[[Los Angeles Times]]|date=January 19, 1948|url-status=live|via=[[Newspapers.com]]|type=clipping|page=9|access-date=November 21, 2019|archive-date=November 21, 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191121161339/https://www.newspapers.com/clip/39377791/3083_see_west_grids_top_east/}}</ref> Mann was also selected by the [[Associated Press]] as a first-team end for its All-Big Nine team.<ref>{{cite news|title=Chappuis, Elliott, Yerges, Mann Named on First Team of All-Big Nine Gridders|newspaper=[[The Michigan Daily]]|date=November 25, 1947|page=3|url=https://digital.bentley.umich.edu/midaily/mdp.39015071756220/365|access-date=February 6, 2020|via=[[Bentley Historical Library]]|url-status=live|agency=[[Associated Press]]|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200206213752/https://digital.bentley.umich.edu/midaily/mdp.39015071756220/365|archive-date=February 6, 2020}}</ref> He was also selected as a second-team [[1947 College Football All-America Team|All-American]] by the Associated Press and the [[Football Writers Association of America]], and Michigan coach Crisler called him \"the greatest pass receiver he has ever coached\".<ref>{{cite news|title=A-A Polls Bypass 'M' Specialists|newspaper=[[The Michigan Daily]]|last=Widenthal|first=Bud|date=January 1, 1948|page=4|url-status=live|access-date=February 6, 2020|url=https://digital.bentley.umich.edu/midaily/mdp.39015071756220/508|via=[[Bentley Historical Library]]|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200206213600/https://digital.bentley.umich.edu/midaily/mdp.39015071756220/508|archive-date=February 6, 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Professional football==\n\n===Detroit Lions===\nIn February 1948, Mann traveled to New York and met with [[New York Yankees (AAFC)|New York Yankees]] coach [[Ray Flaherty]]. Mann said at the time that he would like to play for the Yankees, but was reluctant to agree to any terms as he was expecting to receive feelers from several other teams in the [[All-America Football Conference]] (AAFC) and [[National Football League]] (NFL).<ref>{{cite news|title=Bob Mann, Ford Weigh Pro Football Careers|newspaper=[[Baltimore Afro-American|The Afro American]]|date=February 7, 1948|url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?id=zNMmAAAAIBAJ&sjid=fAIGAAAAIBAJ&pg=4029,862098&dq=bob-mann+football&hl=en|access-date=November 21, 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181004145950/https://news.google.com/newspapers?id=zNMmAAAAIBAJ&sjid=fAIGAAAAIBAJ&pg=4029,862098&dq=bob-mann+football&hl=en|archive-date=October 4, 2018|url-status=live|via=[[Google News Archives]]}}</ref> In April 1948, Mann signed with the [[Detroit Lions]] of the NFL;<ref>{{Cite news | title = Mann signs with Lions| date = April 21, 1948| access-date = November 22, 2019| newspaper = [[Detroit Free Press]]| page = 20| url = https://www.newspapers.com/clip/21069682/mann_signs_with_lions/| archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20191122154650/https://www.newspapers.com/clip/21069682/mann_signs_with_lions/| archive-date = November 22, 2019| url-status=live | via = [[Newspapers.com]]|type=clipping}}</ref> his first NFL contract was for $7,500.<ref name=\"EMBODY\"/> He was also hired to a sales position at the [[Goebel Brewing Company]], which was owned by Lions' president Edwin J. Anderson.<ref name=\"PIONEER\"/> At the time, Detroit's new head coach [[Bo McMillin]]<ref>{{Cite news | url = https://www.newspapers.com/clip/39431950/mmillin_signs_as_new_coach_of_pro/ | via = [[Newspapers.com]]|type=clipping | df = mdy | url-status = live | newspaper = [[South Bend Tribune]] | agency = [[Associated Press]] | page = 1 | title = M'Millin Signs as New Coach of Pro Eleven | date = February 19, 1948 | access-date = November 22, 2019 | archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20191122162255/https://www.newspapers.com/clip/39431950/mmillin_signs_as_new_coach_of_pro/| archive-date = November 22, 2019}}</ref> said, \"We're tickled to get Mann. We've been after his name on a Detroit contract ever since I came here as a coach. We know he will be a valuable professional performer\".<ref name=Signs>{{cite news|title=Detroit Lions Sign Bob Mann|newspaper=[[Tampa Bay Times|St. Petersburg Times]]|date=April 23, 1948|url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?id=7BgLAAAAIBAJ&sjid=Fk8DAAAAIBAJ&pg=5716,800272&dq=bob-mann&hl=en|access-date=November 21, 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181004145950/https://news.google.com/newspapers?id=7BgLAAAAIBAJ&sjid=Fk8DAAAAIBAJ&pg=5716,800272&dq=bob-mann&hl=en|archive-date=October 4, 2018|url-status=live|via=[[Google News Archive]]}}</ref>\n\n====1948 season====\n[[File:BobMann1948Bowman.jpg|thumb|right|Mann's 1948 [[Bowman Gum|Bowman]] football card|alt=A black and white photo of Mann posing catching a football with one hand]]\nAs a rookie in 1948, Mann became the first African American to play for the Lions; halfback [[Mel Groomes]] also played for the Lions in 1948.<ref name=\"FIRST\"/> Although team owners denied the existence of a ban, no African American had played in the NFL between 1933 and 1945.<ref name=\"PIONEER1\">{{Cite news | first = Bill| last = Dow| title = Mann pioneer player in NFL: Part 1| date = January 11, 2002| access-date = November 22, 2019| url-status=live | newspaper = [[Detroit Free Press]]| page = 1D| url = https://www.newspapers.com/clip/24262923/mann_pioneer_player_in_nfl/| archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20191122153444/https://www.newspapers.com/clip/24262923/mann_pioneer_player_in_nfl/| archive-date = November 22, 2019| via = [[Newspapers.com]]|type=clipping}}</ref> Teams in the rival AAFC were much more willing to sign African American players. Even after African American players began appearing in NFL playing rosters, it took many years for them to be given the same opportunities as white players.{{sfn|Piascik|2007|p=190}}\n\nMann appeared in all 12 games for the Lions, though none as a starter. Despite his role as a backup, Mann finished the season with 33 catches for 560 yards, ranking him seventh in the NFL in receiving yards and fourth in yards per reception.<ref name=PFR>{{cite web|title=Bob Mann profile|publisher=Sports Reference LLC.|url=https://www.pro-football-reference.com/players/M/MannBo00.htm|access-date=November 21, 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100913051639/http://www.pro-football-reference.com/players/M/MannBo00.htm|archive-date=September 13, 2010|url-status=live}}</ref> In December 1948, Mann joined [[Jesse Owens]]' Olympians professional basketball team in Cleveland. He had played two years of college basketball at Hampton Institute.<ref>{{cite news|title=Bob Mann Joins Owens' Professional Cage Team|url = https://www.newspapers.com/clip/40167617/bob_mann_joins_owens_professional_cage/ | agency = [[Associated Press]] | newspaper=[[Lansing State Journal]]|date=December 19, 1948|url-status=live|archive-date=December 6, 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191206173730/https://www.newspapers.com/clip/40167617/bob_mann_joins_owens_professional_cage/|access-date=December 6, 2019|via=[[Newspapers.com]]|page=3|type=clipping}}</ref>\n\n====1949 season====\nIn the preseason before the [[1949 NFL season]], the Lions played an [[exhibition game]] against the [[Philadelphia Eagles]] in [[New Orleans]]. Coach McMillin met with the Lions' African American players, including Mann, and explained that due to racial issues, they would not be able to play in the game.<ref name=\"PIONEER\"/> McMillin thought it would be best for everyone to not incite any further racial issues in the city.<ref name=\"EMBODY\"/>\n\nOn December 11, 1949, Mann was credited with eight catches for 182 yards and two touchdowns (including a 64-yard touchdown pass from [[Frank Tripucka]] in the first quarter and a 41-yard touchdown pass in the fourth quarter) against the [[Green Bay Packers]].<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/39346487/packers_end_season_with_21_to_7_loss/|title=Packers End Season With 21 To 7 Loss|newspaper=[[The Sheboygan Press]]|agency=[[Associated Press]]|date=December 12, 1949|page=19|url-status=live|access-date=November 21, 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191120225722/https://www.newspapers.com/clip/39346487/packers_end_season_with_21_to_7_loss/|archive-date=November 20, 2019|via=[[Newspapers.com]]|type=clipping}}</ref> After the game, Mann's wife, described as \"an ardent football fan,\" told statistician Nick Kerbawy that her tally sheet showed that her husband caught nine passes. Kerbawy reexamined the play-by-play account and discovered she was right.<ref>{{Cite news | url = https://www.newspapers.com/clip/40168232/manns_wife_gets_assist/ | title = Mann's Wife Gets Assist | agency = [[United Press International|United Press]] | newspaper = [[Akron Beacon Journal]] | date = December 19, 1949 | url-status = live | page = 27 | access-date = December 6, 2019 | archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20191206175209/https://www.newspapers.com/clip/40168232/manns_wife_gets_assist/ | archive-date = December 6, 2019 | type = clipping | via = [[Newspapers.com]]}}</ref> The new total of nine receptions set a new Lions' record for a single game.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/39399931/mrs_bob_mann_on_the_job_hubby_sets/|title=Mrs. Bob Mann On The Job, Hubby Sets New Record|via=[[Newspapers.com]]|type=clipping|newspaper=[[The Times Herald]]|date=December 14, 1949|page=16|url-status=live|agency=[[Associated Press]]|archive-date=November 21, 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191121224848/https://www.newspapers.com/clip/39399931/mrs_bob_mann_on_the_job_hubby_sets/}}</ref>\n\nDuring the 1949 season, Mann led the NFL with 1,014 receiving yards and 15.4 yards per catch.<ref name=LAT/> He also finished second in receptions with 66 ([[Tom Fears]] set an NFL record in 1949 with 77 receptions).<ref name=LAT/><ref>{{cite news|title=Rams' Fears Tops NFL Pass Catchers|agency=[[Associated Press]]|url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/39375659/rams_fears_tops_nfl_pass_catchers/|via=[[Newspapers.com]]|type=clipping|newspaper=[[Los Angeles Times]]|date=February 23, 1950|access-date=November 21, 2019|page=2|url-status=live|archive-date=November 21, 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191121151757/https://www.newspapers.com/clip/39375659/rams_fears_tops_nfl_pass_catchers/}}</ref> At the time, Mann's season totals in receiving yards and receptions both ranked in the top five all-time.<ref>{{Cite web | url = https://www.pro-football-reference.com/leaders/rec_single_season_1949.htm | title = NFL Single-Season Reception Leaders Through 1949 | publisher = Sports Reference LLC | access-date = December 6, 2019 | url-status = live | archive-date = December 6, 2019| archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20191206172325/https://www.pro-football-reference.com/leaders/rec_single_season_1949.htm}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web | url = https://www.pro-football-reference.com/leaders/rec_yds_single_season_1949.htm | title = NFL Single-Season Receiving Yards Leaders Through 1949 | publisher = Sports Reference LLC | access-date = December 6, 2019 | url-status = live | archive-date = December 6, 2019| archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20191206172504/https://www.pro-football-reference.com/leaders/rec_yds_single_season_1949.htm}}</ref> He also became the first Lions' player to eclipse 1,000 receiving yards in a season.<ref name=\"FIRST\">{{Cite news | url = https://www.latimes.com/archives/la-xpm-2006-oct-25-me-passings25.1-story.html | title = Bob Mann, 82; Detroit Lions\u2019 receiver later became a lawyer | date = October 25, 2006 | access-date = November 22, 2019 | newspaper = [[Los Angeles Times]] | df = mdy | url-status = live | archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20191203203737/https://www.latimes.com/archives/la-xpm-2006-oct-25-me-passings25.1-story.html| archive-date = December 3, 2019}}</ref> Despite leading the NFL in receiving yards, Mann was not selected by the [[United Press International|United Press]] (UP) for either its first- or second-team All-NFL team. Instead, he was named in its \"Honorable Mention\" team.<ref>{{cite news|title=Four Rams Selected on All-NFL Team|newspaper=[[Los Angeles Times]]|url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/39375492/four_rams_selected_on_allnfl_team/|page=1|access-date=November 21, 2019|url-status=live|via=[[Newspapers.com]]|type=clipping|date=December 13, 1949|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191121151312/https://www.newspapers.com/clip/39375492/four_rams_selected_on_allnfl_team/|archive-date=November 21, 2019}}</ref>\n\n====Salary dispute====\nDuring the off-season in 1950, the Lions asked Mann to take a $1,500 pay cut from $7,500 to $6,000.<ref name=LAT/> According to the Lions, the pay cut request was based off of the larger number of available players and the merger of the AAFC and NFL before the start of the season.{{sfn|Ross|2001|p=123-124}} Mann objected and held out, refusing to sign a 1950 contract.<ref>{{cite news|title=Lions Send Mann to Grid Yankees|url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/39384297/lions_send_mann_to_grid_yankees/|via=[[Newspapers.com]]|newspaper=[[The Scranton Times-Tribune|Scrantonian Tribune]]|agency=[[United Press International|United Press]]|date=August 6, 1950|url-status=live|page=37|archive-date=November 21, 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191121182119/https://www.newspapers.com/clip/39384297/lions_send_mann_to_grid_yankees/}}</ref> Further complicating the negotiations, the African American community in Detroit had called for a boycott of Goebel beer, after a bid by an African American group for a distributorship in Detroit's black community had been rejected.{{sfn|Ross|2001|p=123-124}} Mann recalled that Goebels/Lions president Anderson was under the mistaken impression that Mann had met with representatives of the boycott.{{sfn|Piascik|2009|p=31}}{{sfn|Ross|2001|p=123}}\n\n===New York Yankees===\nOn July 31, 1950, Mann became a hold out when he failed to show up on the first day of practice for the Lions.<ref>{{Cite news | url = https://www.newspapers.com/clip/40179021/lions_start_grid_drills/ | title = Lions Start Grid Drills | via = [[Newspapers.com]] | url-status= live | type = clipping | newspaper = [[Lansing State Journal]] | page = 11 | access-date = December 6, 2019 | archive-date = December 6, 2019 | archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20191206212706/https://www.newspapers.com/clip/40179021/lions_start_grid_drills/}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news | url = https://www.newspapers.com/clip/21091473/mann_traded_to_yankees/ | title = Lions Toss In Bob Mann on Layne Deal | date = August 5, 1950 | newspaper = [[Detroit Free Press]] | url-status = live | access-date = December 6, 2019 | page = 12 | via = [[Newspapers.com]] | type = clipping | archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20191206212337/https://www.newspapers.com/clip/21091473/mann_traded_to_yankees/ | archive-date = December 6, 2019}}</ref> That same day, his position for Goebel was terminated.{{sfn|Ross|2001|p=123-124}} Four days later, he was sent to the Yankees in payment for quarterback [[Bobby Layne]].<ref>{{cite news|title=Lions Send Bob Mann to Yanks to Pay for Layne|url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/39376175/lions_send_bob_mann_to_yanks_to_pay_for/|newspaper=[[Chicago Tribune]]|agency=[[Associated Press]]|url-status=live|via=[[Newspapers.com]]|type=clipping|access-date=November 21, 2019|page=4|date=August 5, 1950|archive-date=November 21, 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191121153333/https://www.newspapers.com/clip/39376175/lions_send_bob_mann_to_yanks_to_pay_for/}}</ref> The Lions had previously traded fullback Camp Wilson for Layne, but Wilson refused to report to the Yankees.<ref name=Hold>{{cite news|title=Lions Send Bob Mann To Yanks for Layne|url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/39376341/lions_send_bob_mann_to_yanks_for_layne/|url-status=live|page=8|agency=[[United Press International|United Press]]|newspaper=[[Ironwood Daily Globe]]|date=August 5, 1950|via=[[Newspapers.com]]|type=clipping|archive-date=November 21, 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191121153648/https://www.newspapers.com/clip/39376341/lions_send_bob_mann_to_yanks_for_layne/}}</ref> Mann later recalled that Yankees' coach [[Red Strader]] was upset about the trade. Despite a good training camp, Mann received little playing time in exhibition games. [[John Rauch]], a rookie quarterback, told Mann that he had been ordered not to throw to him. The day after Rauch threw a 50-yard touchdown pass to Mann in a pre-season game against the [[Washington Redskins]], Mann was released by the Yankees.<ref name=\"BLOCKING\"/> He was not picked up by any other team and officially became a free agent.{{sfn|Freedman|2013|p=71}}\n\n====Charges of blackballing====\nThrough the months of September and October 1950, Mann was jobless. At the end of October 1950, Mann publicly charged that he had been \"railroaded\" out of professional football. He claimed that, despite leading the NFL in receiving yards in 1949, the Lions had asked him to take a 20 percent pay cut. After he objected, he contended that the NFL had taken a \"hands off\" policy toward him. Mann publicly stated, \"I must have been blackballed -- it just doesn't make sense that I'm suddenly not good enough to make a single team in the league\".<ref name=LAT>{{cite news|title=Bob Mann Aims Charge that He Was 'Railroaded' at NFL|newspaper=[[Los Angeles Times]]|agency=[[United Press International|United Press]]|date=November 1, 1950|url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/39385357/bob_mann_aims_charge_that_he_was/|via=[[Newspapers.com]]|type=clipping|page=3|access-date=November 21, 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191121184221/https://www.newspapers.com/clip/39385357/bob_mann_aims_charge_that_he_was/|archive-date=November 21, 2019}}</ref> The Lions' response to Mann's charge was a statement that they felt he was too small in stature to be an effective blocker.<ref name=\"BLOCKING\">{{Cite news | url = https://www.newspapers.com/clip/21071367/mann_says_he_was_railroaded/ | type = clipping | title = 'Railroaded' Says Bob Mann | newspaper = [[The Times Herald]] | date = October 31, 1950 | last = Le Donne | first = Jerry | access-date = December 6, 2019 | page = 18 | agency = [[United Press International|United Press]] | via = [[Newspapers.com]] | url-status = live | archive-date = December 6, 2019 | archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20191206171338/https://www.newspapers.com/clip/21071367/mann_says_he_was_railroaded/}}</ref> Mann filed a lawsuit against the NFL based on his belief that NFL owners colluded to avoid signing him. Commissioner [[Bert Bell]] disagreed, even though he was familiar with the way that team owners had colluded to avoid signing black players over the previous decade.{{sfn|Piascik|2009|p=33}}\n\n===Green Bay Packers===\n[[File:Len Ford and Bob Mann (1947).png|thumb|right|Mann (right) with Michigan teammate and future hall of famer [[Len Ford]] (left) in 1947. Both Mann and Ford later played for the Packers, although not at the same time.|alt=Bob Mann and Len Ford wearing suits standing next to each other]]\n\n====1950&ndash;1951====\nMann was signed by the Green Bay Packers on November 25, 1950, ending his suit against the NFL.{{sfn|Piascik|2009|p=33}}<ref>{{cite news|title=Green Bay Packers Sign End Bob Mann|newspaper=[[Wisconsin State Journal]]|url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/39376055/green_bay_packers_sign_end_bob_mann/|agency=[[Associated Press]]|url-status=live|access-date=November 21, 2019|via=[[Newspapers.com]]|type=clipping|date=November 26, 1950|archive-date=November 21, 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191121152917/https://www.newspapers.com/clip/39376055/green_bay_packers_sign_end_bob_mann/|page=3}}</ref> On November 26, 1950, he appeared in the Packers' final home game against the [[San Francisco 49ers]], becoming the first African-American to play for the team.<ref name=\"PACK\"/><ref name=MCT>{{cite news|url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/39346733/first_black_packer_dies/|via=[[Newspapers.com]]|type=clipping|url-status=live|title=First Black Packer Dies|newspaper=[[The Capital Times]]|date=October 24, 2006|page=D2|access-date=November 21, 2019|archive-date=November 20, 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191120230147/https://www.newspapers.com/clip/39346733/first_black_packer_dies/}}</ref> It was later determined that [[Walt Jean]], an [[offensive lineman]] for the Packers in the 1920s, was African American through his father's side of the family. However, this knowledge was not known by Jean's teammates at the time, thus the color barrier was officially broken for the Packers when Mann played his first game with the team.<ref name=\"PACK\"/> Mann ended up playing in three games for the Packers in 1950, catching six passes for 89 yards and one touchdown.<ref name=PFR/>\n\nIn 1951, Mann led the Packers with 50 catches, 696 receiving yards, and eight touchdowns;{{sfn|Freedman|2013|p=91}} he also ranked fourth in the NFL in both receptions and receiving yards that year.<ref name=PFR/><ref name=MCT/> Mann's best performance in 1951 came in an October game against the Philadelphia Eagles; he caught three touchdown passes while the Packers upset the favored Eagles.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/39382852/green_bay_aerial_circus_upsets_eagles/|title=Green Bay Aerial Circus Upsets Eagles, 37&ndash;24|newspaper=[[La Crosse Tribune]]|date=October 15, 1951|agency=[[Associated Press]]|access-date=November 21, 2019|url-status=live|via=[[Newspapers.com]]|type=clipping|page=11|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191121175443/https://www.newspapers.com/clip/39382852/green_bay_aerial_circus_upsets_eagles/|archive-date=November 21, 2019}}</ref> The Packers ended the season with a record of 3&ndash;9, the fourth straight season they won three or less games.<ref>{{Cite web | url = https://www.pro-football-reference.com/teams/gnb/index.htm | url-status = live | title = Green Bay Packers Team Encyclopedia | access-date = December 11, 2019 | publisher = Sports Reference LLC | archive-date = March 24, 2019 | archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20190324190901/https://www.pro-football-reference.com/teams/gnb/index.htm}}</ref>\n\n====1952&ndash;1955====\nIn the [[1952 NFL draft]], the Packers selected [[Rice University]] end [[Billy Howton]] with their second round pick.<ref>{{Cite new | url = https://www.newspapers.com/clip/40380139/five_all_america_stars_top_packer_draft/ | url-status = live | type = clipping | via = [[Newspapers.com]] | title = Five All America Stars Top Packer Draft Picks | last = Daley | first = Art | date = January 18, 1952 | access-date = December 10, 2019 | page = 9 | newspaper = [[Green Bay Press-Gazette]] | archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20191210202750/https://www.newspapers.com/clip/40380139/five_all_america_stars_top_packer_draft/| archive-date = December 10, 2019}}</ref> Howton, who elicited comparisons to Hall of Famer [[Don Hutson]], made an immediate impact on the Packers, leading the league in 1952 with 1,231 receiving yards.<ref>{{Cite news | url = https://www.newspapers.com/clip/40381216/packers_hail_howton_as_new_don_hutson/ | title = Packers Hail Howton As New Don Hutson | newspaper = [[The Terre Haute Tribune]] | date = December 16, 1952 | access-date = December 10, 2019 | url-status = live | type = clipping | via = [[Newspapers.com]] | page = 12 | archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20191210204627/https://www.newspapers.com/clip/40381216/packers_hail_howton_as_new_don_hutson/ | archive-date = December 10, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web | url = https://www.pro-football-reference.com/years/1952/receiving.htm | title = 1952 NFL Receiving | access-date = December 10, 2019 | publisher = Sports Reference LLC | url-status = live | archive-date = December 10, 2019 | archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20190702131316/https://www.pro-football-reference.com/years/1952/receiving.htm}}</ref> Even with Howton in the lineup, Mann had a productive year, recording 30 receptions for 517 yards and six touchdowns.<ref name=PFR/> The Packers improved their record to 6&ndash;6, finishing fourth in [[Eastern and Western Conferences (NFL) 1933\u201369|their conference]].<ref>{{Cite web | url = https://www.pro-football-reference.com/years/1952/index.htm | title = 1952 NFL Standings & Team Stats | publisher = Sports Reference LLC | access-date = December 11, 2019 | url-status = live | archive-date = July 26, 2019 | archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20190726133340/https://www.pro-football-reference.com/years/1952/index.htm}}</ref>\n\nBy 1953, Mann and Howton were considered one of the best receiving duos in the league, though both players missed numerous games due to injury throughout the season.<ref>{{Cite news | url = https://www.newspapers.com/clip/40417742/packers_ace_pass_catchers_reunited/ | newspaper = [[Green Bay Press-Gazette]] | via = [[Newspapers.com]] | title = Packers' Ace Pass Catchers Reunited | date = November 11, 1953 | access-date = December 11, 2019 | url-status = live | type = clipping | last = Daley | first = Art | page = 21 | archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20191211162610/https://www.newspapers.com/clip/40417742/packers_ace_pass_catchers_reunited/ | archive-date = December 11, 2019}}</ref> In ten games, Mann finished the year with 23 receptions for 327 yards and two touchdowns, all of which were second to Howton's totals for the season.<ref>{{Cite web | url = https://web.archive.org/web/20190417230219/https://www.pro-football-reference.com/teams/gnb/1953.htm | title = 1953 Green Bay Packers Statistics & Players | publisher = Sports Reference LLC | access-date = December 11, 2019 | url-status = live | archive-date = April 17, 2019| archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20190417230219/https://www.pro-football-reference.com/teams/gnb/1953.htm}}</ref> Mann's best game in 1953 came in a 21&ndash;21 tie against the [[1953 Chicago Bears season|Chicago Bears]]; according to the ''[[Green Bay Press-Gazette]]'', Mann \"was open all afternoon as the Bears chased Howton\" while catching six passes for 101 yards, including a 45-yard catch.<ref>{{Cite news | url = https://www.newspapers.com/clip/40418669/packers_gain_tie_with_bears_in_last/ | newspaper = [[Green Bay Press-Gazette]] | via = [[Newspapers.com]] | title = Packers Gain Tie With Bears in Last Minute 21&ndash;21 | date = November 9, 1953 | access-date = December 11, 2019 | url-status = live | type = clipping | last = Daley | first = Art | page = 19 | archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20191211165006/https://www.newspapers.com/clip/40418669/packers_gain_tie_with_bears_in_last/ | archive-date = December 11, 2019}}</ref> The Packers ended the year in last place in their conference with a record of 2&ndash;9&ndash;1.<ref>{{cite web | url = https://www.pro-football-reference.com/years/1953/index.htm  | title = 1953 NFL Standings & Team Stats | publisher = Sports Reference LLC | access-date = December 11, 2019 | url-status = live | archive-date = August 19, 2019 | archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20190819053706/https://www.pro-football-reference.com/years/1953/index.htm}}</ref>\n\nIn 1954, Mann played in only two of the Packers' first four games.<ref name=\"PACK\"/> In those two games, he did not record a catch.<ref name=PFR/> He had sustained a knee injury during a preseason game against the [[1954 Philadelphia Eagles season|Philadelphia Eagles]] and was subsequently released by the team six weeks later in October.<ref name=\"PACK\"/> In November 1955, Mann filed a $25,000 breach of contract suit against the Packers. Mann claimed his release was illegal because he was not given written notice by the team.<ref>{{cite news|title=Mann Files $25,000 Suit Against Packers|url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/39375914/mann_files_25000_suit_against_packers/|page=24|via=[[Newspapers.com]]|type=clipping|url-status=live|agency=[[Associated Press]]|newspaper=[[Ironwood Daily Globe]]|date=November 24, 1955|access-date=November 21, 2019|archive-date=November 21, 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191121152534/https://www.newspapers.com/clip/39375914/mann_files_25000_suit_against_packers/}}</ref><ref name=\"ILLEGAL\">{{cite news|title=Suit Filed by Packers' Mann Goes to Detroit|url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/39375801/suit_filed_by_packers_mann_goes_to/|url-status=live|access-date=November 21, 2019|newspaper=[[Chicago Tribune]]|page=4|agency=[[Associated Press]]|via=[[Newspapers.com]]|type=clipping|date=January 5, 1956|archive-date=November 21, 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191121152239/https://www.newspapers.com/clip/39375801/suit_filed_by_packers_mann_goes_to/}}</ref> Mann and the Packers ultimately settled the lawsuit for an undisclosed amount in 1957.<ref>{{Cite web | url = https://books.google.com/books?id=oYZS-PVuqdQC&lpg=PA2827&ots=tyVm4D0qZA&dq=bob%20mann%20packers%20lawsuit&pg=PA2827#v=onepage&q=bob%20mann%20packers%20lawsuit&f=false | via = [[Google Books]] | date = June\u2013August 1957 | title = Hearings Before the Antitrust Subcommittee of the Committee on the Judiciary House of Representatives | publisher = [[United States Congress]] | df = mdy | url-status = live | archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20191126195558/https://books.google.com/books?id=oYZS-PVuqdQC&pg=PA2827&lpg=PA2827&dq=bob+mann+packers+lawsuit&source=bl&ots=tyVm4D0qZA&sig=ACfU3U0-cCrKv7dQEKmGQza7FLnCN_efVw&hl=en&sa=X&ved=2ahUKEwiXzLmS0YjmAhVjFzQIHfpABYYQ6AEwA3oECAkQAQ#v=onepage&q=bob%20mann%20packers%20lawsuit&f=false | archive-date = November 26, 2019 | access-date = November 26, 2019}}</ref> Mann's knee injury forced him to retire from professional football.{{sfn|Gulbrandsen|2007|p=62}}\n\n====Race====\nWhen Mann joined the Packers, the city of [[Green Bay, Wisconsin]] had fewer than 20 black residents. Even with this lack of racial diversity, Mann's time with the Packers was largely free of overt racial incidents.{{sfn|Maxymuk|2003|p=352}} However, racial issues often arose when Mann traveled to other cities with the team.{{sfn|Freedman|2013|p=71}} ''[[Green Bay Gazette]]'' sports writer Art Daley recalled a story involving Mann and teammate [[Dick the Bruiser|Dick Afflis]], who later became known in professional wrestling as \"Dick the Bruiser\". The Packers stayed at a Baltimore hotel that would not allow Mann to stay with the team on account of its policy prohibiting African-American guests. When Mann left to go to another hotel, the {{Convert|252|lb|adj=on}} Afflis left with him. When a cab driver told Afflis that he would not drive Mann because of his race, Afflis grabbed the driver by the shirt and said, \"You will take him wherever he wants to go\".<ref name=NB/> Multiple white teammates reached out to Mann to welcome him after he signed with the Packers and coach [[Gene Ronzani]] gave him additional travel privileges to Milwaukee and Chicago.{{sfn|Maxymuk|2003|p=352}} Overall, Mann enjoyed his time in Green Bay, saying \"I never had any problems. Everyone treated me well\".<ref name=\"VANDER\"/>\n\n====Legacy====\nMann compiled 109 catches for 1,629 yards and 17 touchdowns over his five seasons with the Packers.{{sfn|Maxymuk|2003|p=352}} He was inducted into the [[Green Bay Packers Hall of Fame]] in 1988 in recognition of his contributions to the team.<ref name=GBHOF>{{cite news | title = Packers' first black downplays role | newspaper = [[Green Bay Press-Gazette]] | last = Egle | first = Jim | date = February 13, 1988 | page = 1C | type = clipping | url = https://www.newspapers.com/clip/43750014/packers_first_black_downplays_role/ | via = [[Newspapers.com]] | url-status = live | archive-date = February 7, 2020 | archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20200207001114/https://www.newspapers.com/clip/43750014/packers_first_black_downplays_role/}}</ref> His impact was largely felt off the field though, with the ''[[Detroit Free Press]]'' writing that Mann was a \"pioneer\" wherever he played football, breaking multiple color barriers and doing so in a \"dignified and friendly manner\" that showed his \"strength and determination\".<ref name=\"PIONEER\"/> Packers' team historian Cliff Christl noted that \"Mann endured unimaginable obstacles just to gain [the] opportunity\" to play professional football.<ref name=\"PACK\"/>\n\n==Legal career and personal life==\nAfter retiring from football, Mann returned to Detroit where he worked in real estate sales for the next decade.<ref name=PIONEER/><ref name=GBHOF/> He married in 1956, and with his wife, Vera, had two daughters, Marjorie and Marilyn.  In 1966, at age 43, Mann enrolled in night school at [[Detroit College of Law]].<ref name=PIONEER/><ref name=GBHOF/> He graduated from law school in 1970 and worked as a criminal defense lawyer for over 30 years in [[Detroit]], heading the firm of Robert Mann & Associates.<ref name=PIONEER/><ref name=\"DEAD82\">{{Cite news | title = Ex-Lion, U-M receiver Mann, 82| date = October 25, 2006| access-date = November 22, 2019| url-status=live | newspaper = [[Detroit Free Press]]| page = 2E| url = https://www.newspapers.com/clip/24262849/exlion_um_receiver_mann_82/| archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20191122153333/https://www.newspapers.com/clip/24262849/exlion_um_receiver_mann_82/| archive-date = November 22, 2019| via = [[Newspapers.com]]|type=clipping}}</ref> Mann's law office was located a few blocks from the Detroit Lions' [[Ford Field]].<ref name=\"VANDER\">{{Cite news | last = Vandermause|first = Mike|title=Remembering Bob Mann: 1924-2006|newspaper=[[Green Bay Press-Gazette]]|date=October 24, 2006|page=C-2|url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/24266160/remembering_bob_mann/|via=[[Newspapers.com]]|type=clipping|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191122202346/https://www.newspapers.com/clip/24266160/remembering_bob_mann/|archive-date=November 22, 2019|access-date=November 22, 2019 | url-status=live}}</ref> At the Lions' first regular season game at Ford Field on September 22, 2002, Mann was the Lions' honorary captain.<ref name=NB/> Mann died in October 2006 at age 82, survived by his wife and two daughters.<ref name=\"DEAD82\"/>\n\n==References==\n===Sources===\n{{Reflist}}\n===Bibliography===\n{{Refbegin}}\n*{{cite book|last=Freedman|first=Lew|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=T030AwAAQBAJ&newbks=1&newbks_redir=0&lpg=PA1&dq=The%20Packers%20Experience%3A%20A%20Year-by-Year%20Chronicle%20of%20the%20Green%20Bay%20Packers&pg=PA71#v=onepage&q=Bob%20Mann&f=false|via=[[Google Books]]|title=The Packers Experience: A Year-by-Year Chronicle of the Green Bay Packers|publisher=[[MVP Books]]|location=[[Minneapolis, Minnesota|Minneapolis, MN]]|year=2013|isbn=978-0760344507|pages=240|ref=harv}}\n*{{cite book|last=Gulbrandsen|first=Don|title=Green Bay Packers: The Complete Illustrated History|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=PpXQ19EQMzcC&newbks=1&newbks_redir=0&lpg=PP1&dq=Green%20Bay%20Packers%3A%20The%20Complete%20Illustrated%20History&pg=PA63#v=onepage&q=Bob%20Mann&f=false|via=[[Google Books]]|publisher=[[Voyageur Press]]|location=[[St. Paul, Minnesota|St. Paul, MN]]|year=2007|isbn=978-0760331392|pages=208|ref=harv}}\n*{{Cite book | title = Packers by the Numbers: Jersey Numbers and the Players who Wore Them | url = https://books.google.com/books?id=m9o2_k8zu4QC&newbks=1&newbks_redir=0&lpg=PP1&dq=Packers%20by%20the%20Numbers%3A%20Jersey%20Numbers%20and%20the%20Players%20who%20Wore%20Them&pg=PA351#v=onepage&q=Bob%20Mann&f=false| via = [[Google Books]] | last = Maxymuk | first = John | year = 2003 | publisher = Big Earth Publishing | pages = 452 | ref = harv | location = [[Boulder, Colorado|Boulder, CO]]|isbn=978-1879483903}}\n*{{cite book|last=Piascik|first=Andy|title=The Best Show in Football: The 1946\u20131955 Cleveland Browns\u2014Pro Football's Greatest Dynasty|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=UXKX316bzU4C&newbks=1&newbks_redir=0&lpg=PP1&dq=The%20Best%20Show%20in%20Football%3A%20The%201946%E2%80%931955%20Cleveland%20Browns%E2%80%94Pro%20Football's%20Greatest%20Dynasty&pg=PA190#v=onepage&q=Bob%20Mann&f=false|via=[[Google Books]]|publisher=[[Taylor Trade Publishing]]|location=[[Lanham, Maryland|Lanham, MA]]|year=2007|isbn=978-1589793606|pages=430|ref=harv}}\n*{{cite book|last=Piascik|first=Andy|title=Gridiron Gauntlet: The Story of the Men Who Integrated Pro Football, In Their Own Words|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=f8SvKb4Gr5YC&newbks=1&newbks_redir=0&lpg=PP1&dq=Gridiron%20Gauntlet%3A%20The%20Story%20of%20the%20Men%20Who%20Integrated%20Pro%20Football%2C%20In%20Their%20Own%20Words&pg=PA31#v=onepage&q=Bob%20Mann&f=false|via=[[Google Books]]|publisher=[[Taylor Trade Publishing]]|location=[[Lanham, Maryland|Lanham, MA]]|year=2009|isbn=978-1589796522|pages=258|ref=harv}}\n*{{cite book|last=Ross|first=Charles K.|title=Outside the Lines: African Americans and the Integration of the National Football League|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=56oUCgAAQBAJ&newbks=1&newbks_redir=0&lpg=PP1&dq=Outside%20the%20Lines%3A%20African%20Americans%20and%20the%20Integration%20of%20the%20National%20Football%20League&pg=PA123#v=onepage&q=Bob%20Mann&f=false|via=[[Google Books]]|publisher=[[New York University Press]]|location=[[New York City|New York, NY]]|year=2001|isbn=978-0814774960|pages=220|ref=harv}}\n{{Refend}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons category}}\n* {{Find a Grave|16317197}}\n\n{{Navboxes| list1 =\n{{1947 Michigan Wolverines football navbox}}\n{{Green Bay Packers HOF}}\n{{NFL receiving yardage leaders}}\n}}\n{{Authority control}}\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Mann, Bob}}\n[[Category:1924 births]]\n[[Category:2006 deaths]]\n[[Category:American football ends]]\n[[Category:Detroit Lions players]]\n[[Category:Green Bay Packers players]]\n[[Category:Michigan Wolverines football players]]\n[[Category:Detroit College of Law alumni]]\n[[Category:Lawyers from Detroit]]\n[[Category:Sportspeople from Detroit]]\n[[Category:Sportspeople from New Bern, North Carolina]]\n[[Category:Players of American football from North Carolina]]\n[[Category:African-American players of American football]]\n", "name_user": "Gonzo fan2007", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eLegal career and personal life:link", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Bob_Mann_(American_football)"}
{"title_page": "2020 United States Census", "text_new": "{{Use American English|date = March 2019}}\n{{Short description|24th national census of the United States, planned for April 1, 2020}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=April 2019}}\n{{Infobox census\n| name = Twenty-fourth Census<br />of the United States\n| logo = Seal of the United States Census Bureau.svg\n| logo_caption = Seal of the [[United States Census Bureau|U.S. Census Bureau]]\n| image = US-Census-2020Logo.png\n| image_caption = The Census 2020 logo\n| country = United States\n| date = April 1, 2020\n| region_type = state\n| previous_census = 2010 United States Census\n| previous_year = 2010\n| next_census = 2030 United States Census\n| next_year = 2030\n}}\nThe '''United States Census of 2020''' is the twenty-fourth [[United States Census]]. Census Day, the reference day<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://2020census.gov/en/important-dates.html|title=Important Dates|last=Bureau|first=US Census|website=2020Census.gov|language=en|access-date=2020-03-25|quote=April 1 is Census Day, a key reference date for the 2020 Census. ... When you respond to the census, you'll tell the Census Bureau where you live as of April 1, 2020.}}</ref> used for the census, was April 1, 2020.<ref name=\"timeline\">{{cite web|title=Interactive Timeline |url=http://2010.census.gov/2010census/about/timeline-text.php |work=About the 2010 Census |publisher=U.S. Census Bureau |accessdate=June 17, 2011 |year=2011 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20101220032051/http://2010.census.gov/2010census/about/timeline-text.php |archivedate=December 20, 2010 }}</ref> Other than a pilot study during the 2000 census,<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.vox.com/recode/2020/3/12/21168139/2020-census-online-how-to|title=The 2020 census is online. Here\u2019s how to do it|last=Morrison|first=Sara|date=2020-03-12|website=Vox|language=en|access-date=2020-03-25|quote=While the 2020 census has been billed in some places as the first-ever American census with online submissions, including on the census\u2019s own website, this is not quite true. The 2000 census also had an online response option, but it wasn\u2019t publicized. Perhaps as a result, only 63,000 households ended up filling out the 2000 census online. The low response rate was intentional, allowing it to serve as a test run for the 2010 census. Despite the Census Bureau declaring it to be an 'operational success,' the 2010 census didn\u2019t have an online submission option at all. Now, in 2020, the plan is for the majority of responses to come through the online form.}}</ref> this is the first [[United States|U.S.]] census to offer options to respond online or by phone, in addition to the option to respond on a paper form as with previous censuses.<ref>{{cite web |title=2020 Census Operational Plan v.4.0 |url=https://www2.census.gov/programs-surveys/decennial/2020/program-management/planning-docs/2020-oper-plan4.pdf |website=U.S. Census Bureau |accessdate=5 August 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Introduction==\nAs required by the [[United States Constitution]], the U.S. Census has been conducted every 10 years since 1790. The [[2010 United States Census]] was the previous census completed. All persons in the U.S. age 18 years and older are legally obligated to answer census questions, and to do so truthfully ([[Title 13 of the United States Code]]).<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.govinfo.gov/content/pkg/USCODE-2007-title13/pdf/USCODE-2007-title13.pdf|title=Title 13 \u00a7221 of the United States code|date=February 21, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last1=Selby|first1=W. Gardner|title=Americans must answer U.S. Census Bureau survey by law, though agency has not prosecuted since 1970|url=http://www.politifact.com/texas/statements/2014/jan/09/us-census-bureau/americans-must-answer-us-census-bureau-survey-law-/|website=politifact.com|accessdate=January 6, 2017|format=January 9, 2014|quote=Because you are living in the United States, you are required by law to respond to this survey.}}</ref> [[Personally identifiable information]] is private and the Census Bureau will never release it. However, the [[National Archives and Records Administration]] (NARA) would plan to release the original census returns in 2092, if the [[United States Census Bureau#Data stewardship|72-year rule]] is not changed before then.<ref>{{Cite web|title = The \"72-Year Rule\" \u2013 History \u2013 U.S. Census Bureau|url = https://www.census.gov/history/www/genealogy/decennial_census_records/the_72_year_rule_1.html |website=Census.gov |accessdate = October 26, 2015|first = US Census Bureau, Census History Staff|last = PIO}}</ref>\n[[File:2020 Census Envelope Front and back.jpg|thumb|right|The envelope used to hold the invitation to respond to the 2020 Census]]\nIn 2020, the United States population is projected to be 329.5 million,<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.census.gov/popclock/|title=Population Clock|first = US Census Bureau|last = PIO|website=Census.gov |accessdate = March 22, 2020}}</ref> a 6.7% increase from the [[2010 United States Census|2010 Census]].\n\n== Purpose of the Census ==\n\n=== Reapportionment ===\nThe results of the 2020 census will determine the number of seats for each state in the [[United States House of Representatives|House of Representatives]], which mirrors the number of delegates for each state in the [[United States Electoral College|Electoral College]] (less the two electoral votes allocated to each states regardless of population), for elections in 2022 to 2030.\n\nForecasters have projected which states will gain or lose seats due to the 2020 reapportionment. According to these estimates,\n* [[New York (state)|New York]] is likely to lose 1 or 2 seats;\n* [[Alabama]], [[Illinois]], [[Michigan]], [[Ohio]], [[Pennsylvania]], [[Rhode Island]] and [[West Virginia]] are likely to lose 1 seat;\n* [[California]] and [[Minnesota]] may lose 1 seat or remain the same;\n* [[Montana]] may gain one seat or remain the same;\n* [[Arizona]], [[Colorado]], [[North Carolina]] and [[Oregon]] are likely to gain 1 seat;\n* [[Florida]] is likely to gain 2 seats;\n* [[Texas]] is likely to gain 3 seats.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Cea |first1=Brianna |title=Potential Shifts in Political Power after the 2020 Census {{!}} Brennan Center for Justice |url=https://www.brennancenter.org/potential-shifts-political-power-after-2020-census |website=www.brennancenter.org |accessdate=11 July 2019 |language=en}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |last1=Tippett |first1=Rebecca |title=2020 Congressional Reapportionment: An Update |url=https://demography.cpc.unc.edu/2017/12/21/2020-congressional-reapportionment-an-update/ |website=Carolina Demography |accessdate=11 July 2019 |date=21 December 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=2020 Reapportionment Forecast \u2013 Total Population \u2013 2018 Estimates |url=https://fairlines.org/blog/apportionment/2020-reapportionment-forecast-total-population-2018-estimates/ |website=fairlines.org |accessdate=11 July 2019 |language=en}}</ref>\n\n=== Redistricting ===\n{{See also|2020 United States redistricting cycle}}\nState and local officials use census counts to redraw boundaries for districts like congressional districts ([[redistricting]]), state legislative districts, and school districts.\n\n=== Census data as the basis for federal funding distribution ===\nDozens of federal programs use census data to help direct funding to state and local areas.  Census results help determine how more than $675 billion in federal funding is allocated to states and communities each year for roads, schools, hospitals (health clinics), emergency services, and more.<ref>{{cite web |title=Uses of Census Bureau Data in Federal Funds Distribution |url=https://www.census.gov/library/working-papers/2017/decennial/census-data-federal-funds.html |website=U.S. Census Bureau |accessdate=5 August 2019}}</ref>\n\n== Major design changes for 2020 ==\nThe 2020 Census is the first U.S. census to offer a full Internet response option and the first to extensively use technology\u2014instead of paper\u2014to manage and conduct field work. \n\nKey design changes include:<ref>{{cite web |title=2020 Census Operational Plan v.4.0 |url=https://www2.census.gov/programs-surveys/decennial/2020/program-management/planning-docs/2020-oper-plan4.pdf |website=U.S. Census Bureau |accessdate=5 August 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=Innovative Technologies Ensure a Complete and Accurate Census |url=https://www.census.gov/library/visualizations/2017/comm/technology-2020-census.html |website=U.S. Census Bureau |accessdate=5 August 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last1=Mellnick |first1=Ted |last2=Fischer-Baum |first2=Reuben |title=What's New for the 2020 Census? |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/graphics/2019/national/census-2020-technology/ |accessdate=5 August 2019 |agency=The Washington Post |date=2 April 2019}}</ref>\n* Three response options: Internet, paper, and phone. Ultimately, every household will get a paper form if they don\u2019t respond online. Households in low-Internet areas will receive a paper form from the start.\n* Multiple languages: In addition to English, respondents can complete the census in 12 other languages online or by phone. In addition, language guides, language glossaries, and language identification cards will be provided in 59 non-English languages.\n* In-office address canvassing: In the 2010 and earlier censuses, census workers walked every street in America to verify addresses on the ground. The 2020 Census uses satellite and GPS imagery to identify those areas where housing is changing, and assigns workers to verify those addresses in person.\n* Digital case management: Census takers will use secure smartphones to get daily assignments, navigate to interviews, communicate with supervisors and submit timesheets. Special software is designed to optimize assignments, streamline management, flag issues immediately, and reduce unnecessary follow-up visits.\n* Streamlined follow-up visits using existing data sources: The 2020 Census will use existing government and third-party data to identify vacant households, to predict the best time of day to visit a particular household, and to count and provide characteristics for the people in the household after multiple attempts using existing high-quality data from trusted sources.\n\n== Questions on the Census and data uses ==\n[[File:2020 census questionnaire.jpg|thumb|Paper questionnaire and return envelope]]\nAs required by the Census Act,<ref>{{cite web |title=Title 13, U.S.C., Section 141 |url=https://www.law.cornell.edu/uscode/text/13/141 |accessdate=5 August 2019}}</ref> the U.S. Census Bureau submitted a list of questions to Congress on March 29, 2018.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Wang |first1=Hansi Lo |title=The 2020 Census Questions Every U.S Household Will Be Asked, Annotated |url=https://www.npr.org/2018/03/29/598018163/census-bureau-releases-2020-census-questions-including-1-on-citizenship |accessdate=5 August 2019 |publisher=NPR}}</ref> Based on those questions and a subsequent executive order, the 2020 Census will ask:<ref>{{cite news |title=Trump backs away from census citizenship question, direct agencies to hand over citizenship information to Commerce |url=https://www.cnn.com/2019/07/11/politics/trump-census-executive-action/index.html |agency=CNN |date=11 July 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=About the Census Questions |url=https://2020census.gov/en/about-questions.html |website=2020census.gov |publisher=U.S. Census Bureau |accessdate=14 August 2019}}</ref>\n\n# The number of people living or staying at your home on April 1, 2020.\n#: Used for the total count and to ensure everyone is counted once, only once, and in the right place according to where they live on Census Day.\n# Whether the home is owned or rented.\n#: Used to produce statistics about homeownership and renters for economic indicators, housing programs and informing planning decisions.\n# The sex of each person in the household.\n#: Used to produce statistics used to plan and fund government programs, enforce laws, regulations, and policies against discrimination.\n# The age of each person in the household.\n#: Used to better understand the size and characteristics of different age groups. Agencies use these data to plan and fund government programs that support specific age groups, including children and older populations.\n# The race of each person in the household.\n#: Used by federal agencies to monitor compliance with anti-discrimination provisions, such as those under the Voting Rights Act and Civil Rights Act.\n# Whether a person in the household is of Hispanic, Latino, or Spanish origin.\n#: Used by federal agencies to monitor compliance with anti-discrimination provisions, such as those under the Voting Rights Act and the Civil Rights Act.\n# The relationship of each person in the household to each other.\n#: Used to plan and fund government programs that support families, including people raising children alone, and other households that qualify for additional assistance.\n\n==2020 Census timeline==\n* January\u2013March 2019: The U.S. Census Bureau opens 39 area census offices.<ref>{{cite web |title=2020 Operational Plan, v.4.0 |url=https://www2.census.gov/programs-surveys/decennial/2020/program-management/planning-docs/2020-oper-plan4.pdf |website=U.S. Census Bureau |accessdate=5 August 2019}}</ref>\n* June\u2013September 2019: The Census Bureau opens the remaining 209 area census offices. The offices support and manage the census takers who work all over the country to conduct the census.\n* August 2019: The Census Bureau conducts the in-field address canvassing operation. Census takers visit areas that have added or lost housing in recent years to ensure that the Census Bureau's address list is up to date. The 2020 Census will be the first modern census that doesn\u2019t verify every address in person, on the ground. Instead, satellite imagery, U.S. Postal Service and other current records will verify most addresses, and will highlight areas where census workers need to verify in-person.\n* January 21, 2020: The Census Bureau begins counting the population in remote Alaska, with [[Toksook Bay]] being the first town to be enumerated.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Wang |first1=Hansi Lo |title=Why the 2020 Census Starts in Alaska's Most Remote, Rural Villages |url=https://www.npr.org/2019/01/21/686963414/why-the-u-s-census-starts-in-alaskas-most-remote-rural-villages |accessdate=5 August 2019 |publisher=NPR |date=21 January 2019}}</ref><ref>The count began on January 21 in [[Toksook Bay]]. {{cite news |url=https://www.bbc.com/news/world-us-canada-51200808 |title=US census kicks off by counting first person in rural Alaska |publisher=BBC News |date=January 22, 2020 }}</ref>\n* April 1, 2020: Census Day is observed nationwide. By this date, households will receive an invitation to participate in the 2020 Census. There are three options for responding: online, by mail, or by phone.\n* April 2020: Census takers begin following up with households around selected colleges and universities. Census takers also begin conducting quality check interviews.\n* May 2020: The Census Bureau begins following up with households that have not responded.\n* December 2020: The Census Bureau delivers apportionment counts to the president.\n\n== Marketing and partnerships ==\n[[File:Census buttons and stickers 20200131-9715.jpg|thumb|Buttons and stickers promoting the 2020 Census]]\nAs in previous censuses, the 2020 Census will rely on a network of trusted voices nationwide to help raise awareness, answer questions, and encourage community members to participate.<ref>{{cite web |title=Partners \u2013 2020 Census |url=https://www.2020census.gov/en/partners |website=U.S. Census Bureau |accessdate=5 August 2019}}</ref>  Hundreds of local \u201ccomplete count committees\u201d are dedicating resources to the efforts nationwide.<ref>{{cite web |title=Complete Count Committees |url=https://www.census.gov/partners/complete-count.html |website=U.S. Census Bureau |accessdate=5 August 2019}}</ref> <ref>{{cite web |title=Complete Count Committees Map |url=https://census.gov/library/visualizations/interactive/2020-complete-count-committees.html |website=U.S. Census Bureau |accessdate=5 August 2019}}</ref>\n\nVMLY&R (formerly [[Young & Rubicam]]) secured the Integrated Communications Contract for the 2020 Census campaign in August of 2016.<ref>{{cite news |title=Y-R Tapped as Lead Agency for 2020 Census |url=https://adage.com/article/agency-news/y-r-wins-2020-census-review/305589 |accessdate=5 August 2019 |date=24 August 2016}}</ref>  As the contract\u2019s primary agency of record, VMLY&R created an integrated team for this project, Team Y&R, which includes subcontractors specializing in minority outreach, digital media, [[earned media]] and more.\n\nIn March 2019, the campaign unveiled the 2020 Census tagline: \u201cShape your future. START HERE.\u201d The tagline was based on research that demonstrated which types of messages will reach and motivate all populations, including segments of the population that are historically hard to count.<ref>{{cite web |title=2020 Census Barriers, Attituded and Motivators Study Survey Report |url=https://www.census.gov/programs-surveys/decennial-census/2020-census/planning-management/final-analysis/2020-report-cbams-study-survey.html |website=U.S. Census Bureau |accessdate=5 August 2019 |date=24 January 2019}}</ref> <ref>{{cite web |title=Census Barriers, Attitudes and Motivators Focus Group Report |url=https://www.census.gov/programs-surveys/decennial-census/2020-census/planning-management/final-analysis/2020-report-cbams-focus-group.html |accessdate=5 August 2019 |date=24 January 2019}}</ref>\n\n== Census jobs ==\n[[File:2020 Census Hiring Pamphlet.jpg|thumb|right|The 2020 United States Census hiring pamphlet]]\nThe 2020 Census will hire about 500,000 temporary workers for jobs that include census takers, address listers, office staff, partnership specialists and more.  Candidates can apply online at [http://2020census.gov/jobs 2020census.gov/jobs] or [https://www.usajobs.gov/Search/?k=census USAjobs.gov].\n\nCandidates must:\n* Be 18 or older, have a valid Social Security number, be a U.S. citizen, and have a valid email address.\n* Complete a job application and answer applicant assessment questions.\n* For many jobs, have a valid driver\u2019s license and a vehicle, unless public transportation is readily available.\n* Have access to a computer with Internet access and an email account to complete training. Hired census workers will be paid for training at a training pay rate.\n* Pass an FBI background and fingerprint check.\n* Follow strict guidelines and confidentiality laws. All persons hired must take a lifetime oath to protect the confidentiality of the data they see.\n\n== Implementation problems ==\nThe printing company [[Cenveo]] won the $61 million contract in October 2017 to produce census forms and reminders, but went bankrupt less than four months later.  The Inspector General of the [[U.S. Government Publishing Office]] said the agency failed to check the company's financial status, and improperly allowed the company to lower its bid after other bids were unsealed.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.npr.org/2018/07/31/634383446/officials-botched-2020-census-printing-contract-report-finds|title=Officials Botched 2020 Census Printing Contract, Report Finds|website=NPR.org}}</ref>\n\nThe [[2020 coronavirus pandemic in the United States|Coronavirus pandemic]] caused delays to Census field operations and counts of the homeless and people living in group quarters. {{As of|2020|4|1|df=US}}, Census Day, the Census Bureau still vowed to complete the count by the end of the year.<ref name=\"sfgate-1apr2020\">{{cite news |last1=Schneider |first1=Mike |title=Census Day arrives with U.S. almost paralyzed by coronavirus |url=https://www.sfgate.com/nation/article/Census-Day-arrives-with-U-S-almost-paralyzed-by-15172249.php |accessdate=April 2, 2020 |work=[[San Francisco Chronicle]] |date=April 1, 2020}}</ref>\n\n== Citizenship question debate ==\nThe U.S. decennial census is used to determine federal funds, grants and support to states. The Census Bureau had included a citizenship question until 1950 when it was removed, though it continued to include a question asking about place of birth.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.npr.org/2018/03/27/597436512/fact-check-has-citizenship-been-a-standard-census-question/|title=FACT CHECK: Has Citizenship Been A Standard Census Question?|author=|date=|website=npr.org}}</ref> In a January 2018 memo, an initial evaluation by Census Bureau officials advised against such a question, saying that compiling citizenship data from existing administrative records is more accurate and far less expensive. However, [[Wilbur Ross]], [[Secretary of Commerce|secretary]] of the [[United States Department of Commerce]] which oversees the Census Bureau, decided the administrative approach alone would not be sufficient.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Wallace |first1=Gregory |title=Here's how the Census Bureau can find out who's a citizen |url=https://www.cnn.com/2019/07/11/politics/census-citizenship-question-alternatives/index.html |accessdate=July 11, 2019 |publisher=CNN |date=July 11, 2019}}</ref> The Census Bureau announced in March 2018 its plan to add a question related to citizenship for the 2020 census: \"Is this person a citizen of the United States?\".<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.npr.org/2018/03/29/598018163/census-bureau-releases-2020-census-questions-including-1-on-citizenship|title=The 2020 Census Questions Every U.S Household Will Be Asked, Annotated|work=NPR.org|access-date=November 3, 2018|language=en}}</ref><ref name=\":0\">{{Cite web|url=https://www2.census.gov/library/publications/decennial/2020/operations/planned-questions-2020-acs.pdf|title=Questions Planned for the 2020 Census and American Community Survey|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180330204825/https://www2.census.gov/library/publications/decennial/2020/operations/planned-questions-2020-acs.pdf|archive-date=March 30, 2018|url-status=dead}}</ref><ref>{{cite web | url = https://www.cbsnews.com/news/census-citizenship-question-opposition-anti-immigrant/ | title = Addition of citizenship question to Census draws swift opposition | date = March 27, 2018 | accessdate = November 16, 2018 | work = [[CBS News]] }}</ref> For the 2020 Census, Ross stated to Congress that the citizenship numbers were necessary to enforce the [[Voting Rights Act]]'s protection against voting discrimination.<ref name=\":0\" /> Ross falsely stated to Congress that the citizenship question was requested by the Justice Department and approved by him.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.npr.org/2018/07/11/627350553/citizenship-question-controversy-complicating-census-2020-work-bureau-director-s|title=Citizenship Question Controversy Complicating Census 2020 Work, Bureau Director Says|work=NPR.org|access-date=November 3, 2018|language=en}}</ref>\n\nUpon the Bureau's announcement, several state and city officials criticized the decision, reiterating the concern about discouraging participation from immigrants, resulting in undercounting, and questioning the motives of Secretary Ross in adding the question. Three simultaneous separate federal lawsuits came out of this discovery, occurring at the district courts of New York, Maryland, and California.<ref name=\"3 district\"/> During the controversy over the census question, the Census Bureau ran a test census in June 2019 on about 480,000 households to determine what effects adding the census question would have on participation, and to prepare the Bureau, its staffing, and its counting measurements, to handle the potential lack of responses due to the citizenship question.<ref>{{cite web | url = https://www.npr.org/2019/06/13/731629018/as-legal-battle-persists-census-citizenship-question-is-put-to-the-test | title = As Legal Battle Persists, Census Citizenship Question Is Put To The Test | first = Hansi | last = Lo Wang | date = June 13, 2019 | accessdate = July 2, 2019 | work = [[NPR]] }}</ref>\n\nDuring these trials, documents released in May 2019 showed that the late [[Thomas B. Hofeller]], an architect of Republican [[Gerrymandering in the United States|gerrymandering]], had found that adding the census question could help to gerrymander maps that \"would be advantageous to Republicans and non-Hispanic whites\".<ref name=\"nytimes hofeller\"/> Hofeller later wrote the DOJ letter which justified the policy by claiming it was needed to enforce the 1965 Voting Rights Act.<ref name=\"nytimes hofeller\">{{cite web | url = https://www.nytimes.com/2019/05/30/us/census-citizenship-question-hofeller.html | title = Deceased G.O.P. Strategist's Hard Drives Reveal New Details on the Census Citizenship Question | first = Michael | last = Wines | date = May 30, 2019 | accessdate = May 31, 2019 | work = [[The New York Times]]}}</ref> Following this discovery, the [[United States House Committee on Oversight and Reform]] issued subpoenas for the Department of Justice to provide materials related to the census question and to question both Commerce Secretary Wilbur Ross and [[United States Attorney General]] [[William Barr]], seeking action to judge if they are in contempt. The Trump administration on June 12, 2019, asserted [[executive privilege]] over portions of the requested documents.<ref>{{cite web | url = https://www.cnn.com/2019/06/12/politics/house-oversight-contempt-vote-barr-ross/index.html | title = Trump invokes executive privilege ahead of House Oversight contempt vote for Barr, Ross | first1 = Clare | last1 =  Foran | first2 = Lauren | last2= Fox | date = June 12, 2019 | accessdate = June 12, 2019 | work = [[CNN]] }}</ref> As a result, the House Committee subsequently voted along party lines to hold both Ross and Barr in contempt that day.<ref>{{cite web | url = https://www.usatoday.com/story/news/politics/2019/06/12/house-oversight-barr-ross-contempt-defying-census-subpoenas/1433085001/  |title = House panel votes contempt for Attorney General William Barr and Commerce Secretary Wilbur Ross  |first=  Bart | last = Jansen | date = June 12, 2019 | accessdate = June 12, 2019  |work = [[USA Today]] }}</ref> The full House voted to hold Ross and Barr in contempt on July 17, 2019, in a 230\u2013198 vote along party lines. Despite this passage, the measure will likely not have any effect on Ross and Barr unless the Justice Department takes legal actions against Ross or Barr.<ref>{{cite web | url = https://www.cnn.com/2019/07/17/politics/house-contempt-vote-barr-ross-census/index.html | title = House votes to hold Barr, Ross in criminal contempt over census dispute | first1= Clare | last1 = Foran | first2= Ashley | last2= Killough | date = July 17, 2019 | accessdate = July 17, 2019 | work = [[CNN]] }}</ref>\n\n===New York District Court and subsequent Supreme Court case===\n{{seealso|Department of Commerce v. New York}}\nA lawsuit, led by New York state's attorney general [[Barbara Underwood]] and joined by seventeen other states, fifteen cities and other civil rights groups, was filed in the [[United States District Court for the Southern District of New York]]. During the discovery phase of the trial, new information came to light that Ross had had previous discussions with [[Steve Bannon]] before March 2018 with the intent to add the citizenship question, contradicting statements that he had made to Congress in March. This led District Judge [[Jesse M. Furman]] in September 2018 to ask that Ross clear a day in his schedule to give a deposition to the court related to the addition of the census question prior to the planned start of the trial in November.<ref>{{cite web | url = https://www.cbsnews.com/news/census-citizenship-controversy-likely-to-face-new-york-trial/ | title = Census citizenship controversy likely to face New York trial | date = September 15, 2018 | accessdate = November 16, 2018 | publisher = [[Associated Press]] | via = [[CBS News]] }}</ref>\n\nThe Trump administration filed a writ of ''[[mandamus]]'' to the [[Supreme Court of the United States|United States Supreme Court]], requesting that they postpone the trial, and also to defer any involvement with Ross until the start of the trial. The Supreme Court issued an order that allowed the trial ''United States Census Bureau v. State of New York'' to go forward, but agreed to postpone Ross's [[Deposition (law)|deposition]] until after the start of the trial.<ref>{{cite web | url = https://www.cbsnews.com/news/supreme-court-refuses-trump-administration-request-to-delay-trial-on-2020-census-citizenship-question/ | title = Supreme Court refuses Trump administration request to delay trial on 2020 census citizenship question | first = William | last = Hennessy Jr. | date = November 2, 2018 | accessdate = November 16, 2018 | publisher = [[Associated Press]] | via = [[CBS News]] }}</ref> The Supreme Court also agreed to treat the writ of ''mandamus'' as a writ of petition, and granted ''[[certiorari]]'' to review the question raised by the government of whether a district court can request deposition of a high-ranking executive branch official on a matter related to a trial before evidence has been presented.<ref name=\"reuters 2018-11-16\">{{cite web | url = https://www.reuters.com/article/us-usa-congress-subpoenas/house-republican-to-subpoena-ex-fbi-director-comey-former-ag-lynch-idUSKCN1NL2EF | title = Supreme Court to hear census citizenship question dispute | first = Lawrence | last =Hurley | date = November 16, 2018 | accessdate = November 16, 2018 | publisher = [[Reuters]] }}</ref>\n\nJudge Furman ruled in January 2019 that the addition of the citizenship question to the census was unlawful, stating that \"the decision to add a citizenship question to the 2020 Census\u2014even if it did not violate the Constitution itself\u2014was unlawful for a multitude of independent reasons and must be set aside.\"<ref>{{cite web | url =https://www.cnn.com/2019/01/15/politics/census-citizenship-new-york/index.html  |title= Federal judge strikes down effort to add citizenship question to Census | first1= Elizabeth | last1 = Hartfield | first2= Gregory | last2= Wallace | date = January 15, 2019 | accessdate= January 15, 2019 | work = [[CNN]] }}</ref> The Justice department filed a petition for writ of [[certiorari before judgment]] to have the case directly heard by the [[Supreme Court of the United States|Supreme Court]] and bypass the normal appeal that would have been heard by the [[United States Court of Appeals for the Second Circuit|Second Circuit]], given the pending deadline of June 2019 to publish the census forms. The Supreme Court accepted the petition related to Furman's ruling on February 15, 2019, a separate matter from the question of Ross's deposition, and the case's oral arguments were heard on April 23, 2019.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.msn.com/en-us/news/us/supreme-court-will-rule-on-trump-administrations-effort-to-add-question-on-citizenship-to-2020-census/ar-BBTEn6v?O|title=Supreme Court will rule on Trump administration's effort to add question on citizenship to 2020 Census|website=www.msn.com|access-date=February 15, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.cbsnews.com/news/supreme-court-hears-arguments-on-2020-census-citizenship-question/|title=Supreme Court hears arguments on 2020 census citizenship question|website=www.cbsnews.com|language=en-US|access-date=2019-05-29}}</ref>\n\nThe Supreme Court issued its decision on June 27, 2019, rejecting the Trump administration's stated rationale for including the question.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2019/06/27/us/politics/census-citizenship-question-supreme-court.html|title=Supreme Court Leaves Census Question on Citizenship in Doubt|first=Adam|last=Liptak|date=June 27, 2019|publisher=|newspaper=The New York Times}}</ref> While the Court majority agreed that the question was allowable under the Enumeration Act, they also agreed with the ability of the District Court to ask Commerce for further explanation for the question under the [[Administrative Procedure Act (United States)|Administrative Procedures Act]] (APA), and that they agreed with the District Court that the answers Commerce had provided at the time appeared to be \"contrived\" and pretextual, leaving open the possibility that Commerce could offer a better rationale.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2019/06/27/us/politics/census-citizenship-question-supreme-court.html|title=Supreme Court Leaves Census Question on Citizenship in Doubt|last=Liptak|first=Adam|date=2019-06-27|work=[[The New York Times]]|access-date=2019-06-27|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331}}</ref> The case was remanded back to the District Court, to give Commerce the opportunity to provide better explanation for the rationale of the question to the District Court, who would deem if that was sufficient before allowing the question on the census. The question would be allowed on the census only if these steps can be completed before the self-imposed form printing deadline.<ref>{{cite web | url = https://www.usatoday.com/story/news/politics/2019/06/27/2020-census-citizenship-question-supreme-court-avoids-trump-request/1289738001/  |title = Supreme Court orders further fact-finding on controversial 2020 census citizenship question | date = June 27, 2019 | accessdate= June 27, 2019  | work = [[USA Today]] }}</ref> On July 7 the DOJ announced that it was replacing its entire legal team dealing with that question, but on July 9 Furman rejected the DOJ action, saying that reasons must be given for the withdrawal of each attorney and pointing out that the administration had been insisting for months that the question needed to be settled by July 1.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Thomsen |first1=Jacqueline |title=Judge rejects Justice Dept request to pull lawyers from census case |url=https://thehill.com/regulation/court-battles/452288-judge-rejects-justice-dept-request-to-pull-lawyers-from-ny-census |publisher=The Hill |date=July 9, 2019}}</ref>\n\nThe [[American Civil Liberties Union]] (ACLU) has taken steps to introduce the Hofeller evidence into the New York case but it will not be heard until late 2019, after the Census forms are to be published.<ref name=\"thehill 20190625\"/> {{Update inline|date=January 2020}}\n\n===California District Court case===\nThe second suit over the census question came in the [[United States District Court for the Northern District of California]] under Judge [[Richard Seeborg]], raised by the state of California and several cities within it. In March 2019, Seeborg similarly found as Furman had in New York that the addition of the census question was unconstitutional and issued an injunction to block its use.<ref name=\"3 district\"/><ref>{{cite web | url = https://www.npr.org/2019/03/06/698886346/second-judge-blocks-trump-administrations-census-citizenship-question-plans | title = Second Judge Blocks Trump Administration's Census Citizenship Question Plans | first=  Hanso  | last=  Lo Wang | date = March 6, 2019 | accessdate = July 3, 2019 | work = [[NPR]] }}</ref> The government appealed to the [[United States Court of Appeals for the Ninth Circuit|Ninth Circuit]] before the Supreme Court remanded the case.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.brennancenter.org/our-work/court-cases/california-v-ross|title=California v. Ross|website=Brennan Center for Justice|language=en|access-date=2019-11-19}}</ref><ref name=\"cnn 20190709\"/>\n\n===Maryland District Court case===\nA similar question related to the intent of the question was raised by several immigrants-rights groups in the [[United States District Court for the District of Maryland]]. The case was overseen by Judge [[George J. Hazel]] in the District of Maryland. Hazel had found for the pro-immigration groups in April 2019, ruling that the addition of an immigration question to the Census was unconstitutional.<ref name=\"3 district\">{{cite web | url =https://www.cnn.com/2019/04/05/politics/census-citizenship-question-ruling/index.html | title = Third federal judge blocks census citizenship question | first1 = Ariane | last1 = de Vogue | first2= Elizabeth | last2= Hartfield | date = April 5, 2019 | accessdate = April 5, 2019 | work = [[CNN]] }}</ref> The government issued its appeal to the [[United States Court of Appeals for the Fourth Circuit|Fourth Circuit Court of Appeals]].\n\nThe new Hofeller evidence was presented to Hazel as the case was being heard on appeal during June 2019 at the Fourth Circuit. Hazel stated that the new evidence \"raises a substantial issue\" <ref>{{cite web | url = https://www.npr.org/2019/06/19/733583150/judges-order-sets-up-potential-new-block-against-census-citizenship-question | title = Judge's Order Sets Up Potential New Block Against Census Citizenship Question | first = Hansi | last = Lo Wong | date = June 19, 2019 | accessdate = June 20, 2019 | work = [[NPR]] }}</ref> On June 25, 2019, the Fourth Circuit remanded the case back to Hazel's District Court with the newly provided evidence, and to review if the additional evidence showed discriminatory intent. Should Hazel find such intent, it would be possible for him to place an injunction on the addition of the census question during a new discovery phase, regardless of the Supreme Court decision in ''Department of Commerce v. New York''. This action would effectively render the question moot since the Census forms would need to be published at this point without the citizenship question to meet the mailing deadlines.<ref name=\"thehill 20190625\">{{cite web | url = https://thehill.com/regulation/court-battles/450260-appeals-court-sends-census-question-case-to-lower-court | title = Appeals court sends census case to lower court to review discrimination claims | first = Jacqueline | last = Thomsen | date = June 25, 2019 | accessdate = June 25, 2019 | work = [[The Hill (website)|The Hill]] }}</ref>\n\n===Subsequent actions===\nPresident Trump, after the Supreme Court decision in ''Department of Commerce'' was announced, stated his intent to find a way to delay the census as long as possible so that the judicial matter could be resolved.<ref>{{cite web | url = https://www.usatoday.com/story/news/politics/2019/06/27/supreme-court-citizenship-question-trump-wants-delay-census/1581702001/ | title = Trump says he asked lawyers if census could be delayed after Supreme Court decision on citizenship question | first1 = Nicolas | last1 = Wu | first2= Richard | last2= Wolf | date = June 27, 2019 | accessdate = June 27, 2019 | work = [[USA Today]] }}</ref>\nOn July 2, 2019, the [[United States Department of Justice|Department of Justice]] (DOJ) announced that the citizenship question would not be included in the census, and the Commerce Department began printing census forms without a citizenship question.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Marimow |first1=Ann E. |last2=Bahrampour |first2=Tara |title=2020 Census will not include citizenship question, DOJ confirms |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/local/social-issues/2020-census-will-not-include-citizenship-question-doj-confirms/2019/07/02/0067be4a-9c44-11e9-9ed4-c9089972ad5a_story.html |work=Washington Post |date=2 July 2019 |language=en}}</ref> However, the next day, Trump insisted that his administration was \"absolutely moving forward\" with the citizenship question, and the Justice Department confirmed in court that it had been instructed to find a legal way to include it in the census.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Wang |first1=Hansi Lo |last2=Kelly |first2=Amita |title=DOJ Still Looking To Add Census Citizenship Question, Official Tells Court |url=https://www.npr.org/2019/07/03/738139549/trump-digs-in-on-census-citizenship-question-sparking-confusion-and-court-activi |work=NPR.org |date=July 3, 2019 | accessdate = July 3, 2019}}</ref><ref name=\"nytimes 20190703\">{{cite web | url = https://www.nytimes.com/2019/07/03/us/politics/census-citizenship-question.html | title = Justice Department Reverses Course on Citizenship Question on Census, Citing Trump's Orders  | first1 = Michael | last1 = Wines | first2=  Maggie | last2=  Haberman | first3=  Alan | last3 =  Rappeport | date = July 3, 2019 | accessdate = July 3, 2019 | work = [[The New York Times]] }}</ref>\n\nIn response to an order from Judge Hazel, the Justice Department affirmed on July 5, 2019 that it will be seeking a route to add the citizenship question to the census, though at the time did not know which route it would take. Hazel had ordered this response as, if the Department was intending to add the question, he could begin determining a schedule in coordination with Judge Furman in the New York court for further proceedings and discovery in both the New York and Maryland lawsuits.<ref name=\"nytimes 20190703\"/><ref>{{cite web | url = https://www.nytimes.com/2019/07/05/us/census-question.html | title = Trump Administration Pressing Ahead in Efforts to Add Citizenship Question to Census | first = Michael | last=  Wines | date = July 5, 2019 | accessdate = July 5, 2019  |work = [[The New York Times]] }}</ref> On July 7 the DOJ announced its intention to replace its entire legal team on the case,<ref>{{cite web | url = https://www.cnn.com/2019/07/07/politics/doj-new-legal-team-census/index.html | title = DOJ says new legal team will take over census case | first1 = Kaitlan | last1 = Collins | first2=  David | last2= Shortell | first3 = Kate | last3=  Sullivan | date = July 7, 2019 | accessdate = July 7, 2019 | work = [[CNN]] }}</ref> but Furman allowed the DOJ to dismiss only two of its eleven attorneys, writing in the July 9 rejection that the DOJ had \"provide[d] no reasons, let alone 'satisfactory reasons,' for the substitution of counsel\".<ref name=\"cnn 20190709\"/><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.huffpost.com/entry/census-citizenship-case-doj-attorneys_n_5d2509abe4b0cfb595fd62e8|title=Judge Blocks DOJ Request To Switch Lawyers In Census Citizenship Case|last=Levine|first=Sam|date=2019-07-09|website=HuffPost|language=en|access-date=2019-07-10}}</ref> Furman pointed out that the case had already run past the DOJ's own previously requested deadline of July 1 and that replacing counsel would cause further delays.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Thomsen |first1=Jacqueline |title=Judge rejects Justice Dept request to pull lawyers from census case |url=https://thehill.com/regulation/court-battles/452288-judge-rejects-justice-dept-request-to-pull-lawyers-from-ny-census | website = [[The Hill (magazine)|The Hill]] |date=July 9, 2019 | accessdate = July 9, 2019}}</ref><ref name=\"cnn 20190709\">{{cite web | url = https://www.cnn.com/2019/07/09/politics/federal-judge-doj-census-legal-team/index.html |title = Federal judge says DOJ can't swap out its legal team in census case | first = Katelyn | last = Polantz | date = July 9, 2019 | accessdate = July 9, 2019 | work = [[CNN]] }}</ref>\n\nSeparate from the events in the courts, Trump has stated he also considered using an [[executive order]] to place the citizenship question on the census.<ref>{{cite web | url = https://www.cnn.com/2019/07/11/politics/trump-census-executive-action/index.html | title = Trump expected to announce executive action on census | first1 = Jim | last1 = Acosta | first2= Joe | last2 = Johns | first3 = Gregory | last3 =  Wallace | date = July 11, 2019 | accessdate = July 11, 2019  |work = [[CNN]] }}</ref> However, on July 11 he issued Executive Order 13880 directing the Department of Commerce to obtain citizenship data from other federal agencies rather than via the census.<ref>{{cite news |title=Trump backs away from census citizenship question, direct agencies to hand over citizenship information to Commerce |url=https://www.cnn.com/2019/07/11/politics/trump-census-executive-action/index.html |accessdate=July 11, 2019 |issue=July 11, 2019 |publisher=CNN}}</ref> He added that \"we are not backing down in our effort to determine the citizenship status of the United States population\" and that data from other federal agencies would be \"far more accurate\" than a census question.<ref name = Re/> A spokesperson for the Department of Justice said that although the DOJ had agreed with Ross's plan to include the question, \"Today\u2019s Executive Order represents an alternative path to collecting the best citizenship data now available, which is vital for informed policymaking and numerous other reasons.  Accordingly, the Department will promptly inform the courts that the Government will not include a citizenship question on the 2020 decennial census.\u201d<ref name = Re>{{cite news |last1=Re |first1=Gregg |title=Trump, 'not backing down' in effort to count citizens amid census fight, announces executive order |url=https://www.foxnews.com/politics/trump-citizens-executive-order-census-count |accessdate=July 11, 2019 |publisher=Fox News |date=July 11, 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Notes==\n{{notelist}}\nList list list list fires bad list list list list\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* [https://census.gov/2020census/ 2020 Census] from the [[United States Census Bureau]]\n\n{{USCensus}}\n\n[[Category:United States Census]]\n[[Category:Trump administration controversies]]\n[[Category:2020 in American politics|Census 2020]]\n[[Category:2020 censuses|United States]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use American English|date = March 2019}}\n{{Short description|24th national census of the United States, planned for April 1, 2020}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=April 2019}}\n{{Infobox census\n| name = Twenty-fourth Census<br />of the United States\n| logo = Seal of the United States Census Bureau.svg\n| logo_caption = Seal of the [[United States Census Bureau|U.S. Census Bureau]]\n| image = US-Census-2020Logo.png\n| image_caption = The Census 2020 logo\n| country = United States\n| date = April 1, 2020\n| region_type = state\n| previous_census = 2010 United States Census\n| previous_year = 2010\n| next_census = 2030 United States Census\n| next_year = 2030\n}}\nThe '''United States Census of 2020''' is the twenty-fourth [[United States Census]]. Census Day, the reference day<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://2020census.gov/en/important-dates.html|title=Important Dates|last=Bureau|first=US Census|website=2020Census.gov|language=en|access-date=2020-03-25|quote=April 1 is Census Day, a key reference date for the 2020 Census. ... When you respond to the census, you'll tell the Census Bureau where you live as of April 1, 2020.}}</ref> used for the census, was April 1, 2020.<ref name=\"timeline\">{{cite web|title=Interactive Timeline |url=http://2010.census.gov/2010census/about/timeline-text.php |work=About the 2010 Census |publisher=U.S. Census Bureau |accessdate=June 17, 2011 |year=2011 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20101220032051/http://2010.census.gov/2010census/about/timeline-text.php |archivedate=December 20, 2010 }}</ref> Other than a pilot study during the 2000 census,<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.vox.com/recode/2020/3/12/21168139/2020-census-online-how-to|title=The 2020 census is online. Here\u2019s how to do it|last=Morrison|first=Sara|date=2020-03-12|website=Vox|language=en|access-date=2020-03-25|quote=While the 2020 census has been billed in some places as the first-ever American census with online submissions, including on the census\u2019s own website, this is not quite true. The 2000 census also had an online response option, but it wasn\u2019t publicized. Perhaps as a result, only 63,000 households ended up filling out the 2000 census online. The low response rate was intentional, allowing it to serve as a test run for the 2010 census. Despite the Census Bureau declaring it to be an 'operational success,' the 2010 census didn\u2019t have an online submission option at all. Now, in 2020, the plan is for the majority of responses to come through the online form.}}</ref> this is the first [[United States|U.S.]] census to offer options to respond online or by phone, in addition to the option to respond on a paper form as with previous censuses.<ref>{{cite web |title=2020 Census Operational Plan v.4.0 |url=https://www2.census.gov/programs-surveys/decennial/2020/program-management/planning-docs/2020-oper-plan4.pdf |website=U.S. Census Bureau |accessdate=5 August 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Introduction==\nAs required by the [[United States Constitution]], the U.S. Census has been conducted every 10 years since 1790. The [[2010 United States Census]] was the previous census completed. All persons in the U.S. age 18 years and older are legally obligated to answer census questions, and to do so truthfully ([[Title 13 of the United States Code]]).<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.govinfo.gov/content/pkg/USCODE-2007-title13/pdf/USCODE-2007-title13.pdf|title=Title 13 \u00a7221 of the United States code|date=February 21, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last1=Selby|first1=W. Gardner|title=Americans must answer U.S. Census Bureau survey by law, though agency has not prosecuted since 1970|url=http://www.politifact.com/texas/statements/2014/jan/09/us-census-bureau/americans-must-answer-us-census-bureau-survey-law-/|website=politifact.com|accessdate=January 6, 2017|format=January 9, 2014|quote=Because you are living in the United States, you are required by law to respond to this survey.}}</ref> [[Personally identifiable information]] is private and the Census Bureau will never release it. However, the [[National Archives and Records Administration]] (NARA) would plan to release the original census returns in 2092, if the [[United States Census Bureau#Data stewardship|72-year rule]] is not changed before then.<ref>{{Cite web|title = The \"72-Year Rule\" \u2013 History \u2013 U.S. Census Bureau|url = https://www.census.gov/history/www/genealogy/decennial_census_records/the_72_year_rule_1.html |website=Census.gov |accessdate = October 26, 2015|first = US Census Bureau, Census History Staff|last = PIO}}</ref>\n[[File:2020 Census Envelope Front and back.jpg|thumb|right|The envelope used to hold the invitation to respond to the 2020 Census]]\nIn 2020, the United States population is projected to be 329.5 million,<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.census.gov/popclock/|title=Population Clock|first = US Census Bureau|last = PIO|website=Census.gov |accessdate = March 22, 2020}}</ref> a 6.7% increase from the [[2010 United States Census|2010 Census]].\n\n== Purpose of the Census ==\n\n=== Reapportionment ===\nThe results of the 2020 census will determine the number of seats for each state in the [[United States House of Representatives|House of Representatives]], which mirrors the number of delegates for each state in the [[United States Electoral College|Electoral College]] (less the two electoral votes allocated to each states regardless of population), for elections in 2022 to 2030.\n\nForecasters have projected which states will gain or lose seats due to the 2020 reapportionment. According to these estimates,\n* [[New York (state)|New York]] is likely to lose 1 or 2 seats;\n* [[Alabama]], [[Illinois]], [[Michigan]], [[Ohio]], [[Pennsylvania]], [[Rhode Island]] and [[West Virginia]] are likely to lose 1 seat;\n* [[California]] and [[Minnesota]] may lose 1 seat or remain the same;\n* [[Montana]] may gain one seat or remain the same;\n* [[Arizona]], [[Colorado]], [[North Carolina]] and [[Oregon]] are likely to gain 1 seat;\n* [[Florida]] is likely to gain 2 seats;\n* [[Texas]] is likely to gain 3 seats.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Cea |first1=Brianna |title=Potential Shifts in Political Power after the 2020 Census {{!}} Brennan Center for Justice |url=https://www.brennancenter.org/potential-shifts-political-power-after-2020-census |website=www.brennancenter.org |accessdate=11 July 2019 |language=en}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |last1=Tippett |first1=Rebecca |title=2020 Congressional Reapportionment: An Update |url=https://demography.cpc.unc.edu/2017/12/21/2020-congressional-reapportionment-an-update/ |website=Carolina Demography |accessdate=11 July 2019 |date=21 December 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=2020 Reapportionment Forecast \u2013 Total Population \u2013 2018 Estimates |url=https://fairlines.org/blog/apportionment/2020-reapportionment-forecast-total-population-2018-estimates/ |website=fairlines.org |accessdate=11 July 2019 |language=en}}</ref>\n\n=== Redistricting ===\n{{See also|2020 United States redistricting cycle}}\nState and local officials use census counts to redraw boundaries for districts like congressional districts ([[redistricting]]), state legislative districts, and school districts.\n\n=== Census data as the basis for federal funding distribution ===\nDozens of federal programs use census data to help direct funding to state and local areas.  Census results help determine how more than $675 billion in federal funding is allocated to states and communities each year for roads, schools, hospitals (health clinics), emergency services, and more.<ref>{{cite web |title=Uses of Census Bureau Data in Federal Funds Distribution |url=https://www.census.gov/library/working-papers/2017/decennial/census-data-federal-funds.html |website=U.S. Census Bureau |accessdate=5 August 2019}}</ref>\n\n== Major design changes for 2020 ==\nThe 2020 Census is the first U.S. census to offer a full Internet response option and the first to extensively use technology\u2014instead of paper\u2014to manage and conduct field work. \n\nKey design changes include:<ref>{{cite web |title=2020 Census Operational Plan v.4.0 |url=https://www2.census.gov/programs-surveys/decennial/2020/program-management/planning-docs/2020-oper-plan4.pdf |website=U.S. Census Bureau |accessdate=5 August 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=Innovative Technologies Ensure a Complete and Accurate Census |url=https://www.census.gov/library/visualizations/2017/comm/technology-2020-census.html |website=U.S. Census Bureau |accessdate=5 August 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last1=Mellnick |first1=Ted |last2=Fischer-Baum |first2=Reuben |title=What's New for the 2020 Census? |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/graphics/2019/national/census-2020-technology/ |accessdate=5 August 2019 |agency=The Washington Post |date=2 April 2019}}</ref>\n* Three response options: Internet, paper, and phone. Ultimately, every household will get a paper form if they don\u2019t respond online. Households in low-Internet areas will receive a paper form from the start.\n* Multiple languages: In addition to English, respondents can complete the census in 12 other languages online or by phone. In addition, language guides, language glossaries, and language identification cards will be provided in 59 non-English languages.\n* In-office address canvassing: In the 2010 and earlier censuses, census workers walked every street in America to verify addresses on the ground. The 2020 Census uses satellite and GPS imagery to identify those areas where housing is changing, and assigns workers to verify those addresses in person.\n* Digital case management: Census takers will use secure smartphones to get daily assignments, navigate to interviews, communicate with supervisors and submit timesheets. Special software is designed to optimize assignments, streamline management, flag issues immediately, and reduce unnecessary follow-up visits.\n* Streamlined follow-up visits using existing data sources: The 2020 Census will use existing government and third-party data to identify vacant households, to predict the best time of day to visit a particular household, and to count and provide characteristics for the people in the household after multiple attempts using existing high-quality data from trusted sources.\n\n== Questions on the Census and data uses ==\n[[File:2020 census questionnaire.jpg|thumb|Paper questionnaire and return envelope]]\nAs required by the Census Act,<ref>{{cite web |title=Title 13, U.S.C., Section 141 |url=https://www.law.cornell.edu/uscode/text/13/141 |accessdate=5 August 2019}}</ref> the U.S. Census Bureau submitted a list of questions to Congress on March 29, 2018.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Wang |first1=Hansi Lo |title=The 2020 Census Questions Every U.S Household Will Be Asked, Annotated |url=https://www.npr.org/2018/03/29/598018163/census-bureau-releases-2020-census-questions-including-1-on-citizenship |accessdate=5 August 2019 |publisher=NPR}}</ref> Based on those questions and a subsequent executive order, the 2020 Census will ask:<ref>{{cite news |title=Trump backs away from census citizenship question, direct agencies to hand over citizenship information to Commerce |url=https://www.cnn.com/2019/07/11/politics/trump-census-executive-action/index.html |agency=CNN |date=11 July 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=About the Census Questions |url=https://2020census.gov/en/about-questions.html |website=2020census.gov |publisher=U.S. Census Bureau |accessdate=14 August 2019}}</ref>\n\n# The number of people living or staying at your home on April 1, 2020.\n#: Used for the total count and to ensure everyone is counted once, only once, and in the right place according to where they live on Census Day.\n# Whether the home is owned or rented.\n#: Used to produce statistics about homeownership and renters for economic indicators, housing programs and informing planning decisions.\n# The sex of each person in the household.\n#: Used to produce statistics used to plan and fund government programs, enforce laws, regulations, and policies against discrimination.\n# The age of each person in the household.\n#: Used to better understand the size and characteristics of different age groups. Agencies use these data to plan and fund government programs that support specific age groups, including children and older populations.\n# The race of each person in the household.\n#: Used by federal agencies to monitor compliance with anti-discrimination provisions, such as those under the Voting Rights Act and Civil Rights Act.\n# Whether a person in the household is of Hispanic, Latino, or Spanish origin.\n#: Used by federal agencies to monitor compliance with anti-discrimination provisions, such as those under the Voting Rights Act and the Civil Rights Act.\n# The relationship of each person in the household to each other.\n#: Used to plan and fund government programs that support families, including people raising children alone, and other households that qualify for additional assistance.\n\n==2020 Census timeline==\n* January\u2013March 2019: The U.S. Census Bureau opens 39 area census offices.<ref>{{cite web |title=2020 Operational Plan, v.4.0 |url=https://www2.census.gov/programs-surveys/decennial/2020/program-management/planning-docs/2020-oper-plan4.pdf |website=U.S. Census Bureau |accessdate=5 August 2019}}</ref>\n* June\u2013September 2019: The Census Bureau opens the remaining 209 area census offices. The offices support and manage the census takers who work all over the country to conduct the census.\n* August 2019: The Census Bureau conducts the in-field address canvassing operation. Census takers visit areas that have added or lost housing in recent years to ensure that the Census Bureau's address list is up to date. The 2020 Census will be the first modern census that doesn\u2019t verify every address in person, on the ground. Instead, satellite imagery, U.S. Postal Service and other current records will verify most addresses, and will highlight areas where census workers need to verify in-person.\n* January 21, 2020: The Census Bureau begins counting the population in remote Alaska, with [[Toksook Bay]] being the first town to be enumerated.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Wang |first1=Hansi Lo |title=Why the 2020 Census Starts in Alaska's Most Remote, Rural Villages |url=https://www.npr.org/2019/01/21/686963414/why-the-u-s-census-starts-in-alaskas-most-remote-rural-villages |accessdate=5 August 2019 |publisher=NPR |date=21 January 2019}}</ref><ref>The count began on January 21 in [[Toksook Bay]]. {{cite news |url=https://www.bbc.com/news/world-us-canada-51200808 |title=US census kicks off by counting first person in rural Alaska |publisher=BBC News |date=January 22, 2020 }}</ref>\n* April 1, 2020: Census Day is observed nationwide. By this date, households will receive an invitation to participate in the 2020 Census. There are three options for responding: online, by mail, or by phone.\n* April 2020: Census takers begin following up with households around selected colleges and universities. Census takers also begin conducting quality check interviews.\n* May 2020: The Census Bureau begins following up with households that have not responded.\n* December 2020: The Census Bureau delivers apportionment counts to the president.\n\n== Marketing and partnerships ==\n[[File:Census buttons and stickers 20200131-9715.jpg|thumb|Buttons and stickers promoting the 2020 Census]]\nAs in previous censuses, the 2020 Census will rely on a network of trusted voices nationwide to help raise awareness, answer questions, and encourage community members to participate.<ref>{{cite web |title=Partners \u2013 2020 Census |url=https://www.2020census.gov/en/partners |website=U.S. Census Bureau |accessdate=5 August 2019}}</ref>  Hundreds of local \u201ccomplete count committees\u201d are dedicating resources to the efforts nationwide.<ref>{{cite web |title=Complete Count Committees |url=https://www.census.gov/partners/complete-count.html |website=U.S. Census Bureau |accessdate=5 August 2019}}</ref> <ref>{{cite web |title=Complete Count Committees Map |url=https://census.gov/library/visualizations/interactive/2020-complete-count-committees.html |website=U.S. Census Bureau |accessdate=5 August 2019}}</ref>\n\nVMLY&R (formerly [[Young & Rubicam]]) secured the Integrated Communications Contract for the 2020 Census campaign in August of 2016.<ref>{{cite news |title=Y-R Tapped as Lead Agency for 2020 Census |url=https://adage.com/article/agency-news/y-r-wins-2020-census-review/305589 |accessdate=5 August 2019 |date=24 August 2016}}</ref>  As the contract\u2019s primary agency of record, VMLY&R created an integrated team for this project, Team Y&R, which includes subcontractors specializing in minority outreach, digital media, [[earned media]] and more.\n\nIn March 2019, the campaign unveiled the 2020 Census tagline: \u201cShape your future. START HERE.\u201d The tagline was based on research that demonstrated which types of messages will reach and motivate all populations, including segments of the population that are historically hard to count.<ref>{{cite web |title=2020 Census Barriers, Attituded and Motivators Study Survey Report |url=https://www.census.gov/programs-surveys/decennial-census/2020-census/planning-management/final-analysis/2020-report-cbams-study-survey.html |website=U.S. Census Bureau |accessdate=5 August 2019 |date=24 January 2019}}</ref> <ref>{{cite web |title=Census Barriers, Attitudes and Motivators Focus Group Report |url=https://www.census.gov/programs-surveys/decennial-census/2020-census/planning-management/final-analysis/2020-report-cbams-focus-group.html |accessdate=5 August 2019 |date=24 January 2019}}</ref>\n\n== Census jobs ==\n[[File:2020 Census Hiring Pamphlet.jpg|thumb|right|The 2020 United States Census hiring pamphlet]]\nThe 2020 Census will hire about 500,000 temporary workers for jobs that include census takers, address listers, office staff, partnership specialists and more.  Candidates can apply online at [http://2020census.gov/jobs 2020census.gov/jobs] or [https://www.usajobs.gov/Search/?k=census USAjobs.gov].\n\nCandidates must:\n* Be 18 or older, have a valid Social Security number, be a U.S. citizen, and have a valid email address.\n* Complete a job application and answer applicant assessment questions.\n* For many jobs, have a valid driver\u2019s license and a vehicle, unless public transportation is readily available.\n* Have access to a computer with Internet access and an email account to complete training. Hired census workers will be paid for training at a training pay rate.\n* Pass an FBI background and fingerprint check.\n* Follow strict guidelines and confidentiality laws. All persons hired must take a lifetime oath to protect the confidentiality of the data they see.\n\n== Implementation problems ==\nThe printing company [[Cenveo]] won the $61 million contract in October 2017 to produce census forms and reminders, but went bankrupt less than four months later.  The Inspector General of the [[U.S. Government Publishing Office]] said the agency failed to check the company's financial status, and improperly allowed the company to lower its bid after other bids were unsealed.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.npr.org/2018/07/31/634383446/officials-botched-2020-census-printing-contract-report-finds|title=Officials Botched 2020 Census Printing Contract, Report Finds|website=NPR.org}}</ref>\n\nThe [[2020 coronavirus pandemic in the United States|Coronavirus pandemic]] caused delays to Census field operations and counts of the homeless and people living in group quarters. {{As of|2020|4|1|df=US}}, Census Day, the Census Bureau still vowed to complete the count by the end of the year.<ref name=\"sfgate-1apr2020\">{{cite news |last1=Schneider |first1=Mike |title=Census Day arrives with U.S. almost paralyzed by coronavirus |url=https://www.sfgate.com/nation/article/Census-Day-arrives-with-U-S-almost-paralyzed-by-15172249.php |accessdate=April 2, 2020 |work=[[San Francisco Chronicle]] |date=April 1, 2020}}</ref>\n\n== Citizenship question debate ==\nThe U.S. decennial census is used to determine federal funds, grants and support to states. The Census Bureau had included a citizenship question until 1950 when it was removed, though it continued to include a question asking about place of birth.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.npr.org/2018/03/27/597436512/fact-check-has-citizenship-been-a-standard-census-question/|title=FACT CHECK: Has Citizenship Been A Standard Census Question?|author=|date=|website=npr.org}}</ref> In a January 2018 memo, an initial evaluation by Census Bureau officials advised against such a question, saying that compiling citizenship data from existing administrative records is more accurate and far less expensive. However, [[Wilbur Ross]], [[Secretary of Commerce|secretary]] of the [[United States Department of Commerce]] which oversees the Census Bureau, decided the administrative approach alone would not be sufficient.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Wallace |first1=Gregory |title=Here's how the Census Bureau can find out who's a citizen |url=https://www.cnn.com/2019/07/11/politics/census-citizenship-question-alternatives/index.html |accessdate=July 11, 2019 |publisher=CNN |date=July 11, 2019}}</ref> The Census Bureau announced in March 2018 its plan to add a question related to citizenship for the 2020 census: \"Is this person a citizen of the United States?\".<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.npr.org/2018/03/29/598018163/census-bureau-releases-2020-census-questions-including-1-on-citizenship|title=The 2020 Census Questions Every U.S Household Will Be Asked, Annotated|work=NPR.org|access-date=November 3, 2018|language=en}}</ref><ref name=\":0\">{{Cite web|url=https://www2.census.gov/library/publications/decennial/2020/operations/planned-questions-2020-acs.pdf|title=Questions Planned for the 2020 Census and American Community Survey|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180330204825/https://www2.census.gov/library/publications/decennial/2020/operations/planned-questions-2020-acs.pdf|archive-date=March 30, 2018|url-status=dead}}</ref><ref>{{cite web | url = https://www.cbsnews.com/news/census-citizenship-question-opposition-anti-immigrant/ | title = Addition of citizenship question to Census draws swift opposition | date = March 27, 2018 | accessdate = November 16, 2018 | work = [[CBS News]] }}</ref> For the 2020 Census, Ross stated to Congress that the citizenship numbers were necessary to enforce the [[Voting Rights Act]]'s protection against voting discrimination.<ref name=\":0\" /> Ross falsely stated to Congress that the citizenship question was requested by the Justice Department and approved by him.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.npr.org/2018/07/11/627350553/citizenship-question-controversy-complicating-census-2020-work-bureau-director-s|title=Citizenship Question Controversy Complicating Census 2020 Work, Bureau Director Says|work=NPR.org|access-date=November 3, 2018|language=en}}</ref>\n\nUpon the Bureau's announcement, several state and city officials criticized the decision, reiterating the concern about discouraging participation from immigrants, resulting in undercounting, and questioning the motives of Secretary Ross in adding the question. Three simultaneous separate federal lawsuits came out of this discovery, occurring at the district courts of New York, Maryland, and California.<ref name=\"3 district\"/> During the controversy over the census question, the Census Bureau ran a test census in June 2019 on about 480,000 households to determine what effects adding the census question would have on participation, and to prepare the Bureau, its staffing, and its counting measurements, to handle the potential lack of responses due to the citizenship question.<ref>{{cite web | url = https://www.npr.org/2019/06/13/731629018/as-legal-battle-persists-census-citizenship-question-is-put-to-the-test | title = As Legal Battle Persists, Census Citizenship Question Is Put To The Test | first = Hansi | last = Lo Wang | date = June 13, 2019 | accessdate = July 2, 2019 | work = [[NPR]] }}</ref>\n\nDuring these trials, documents released in May 2019 showed that the late [[Thomas B. Hofeller]], an architect of Republican [[Gerrymandering in the United States|gerrymandering]], had found that adding the census question could help to gerrymander maps that \"would be advantageous to Republicans and non-Hispanic whites\".<ref name=\"nytimes hofeller\"/> Hofeller later wrote the DOJ letter which justified the policy by claiming it was needed to enforce the 1965 Voting Rights Act.<ref name=\"nytimes hofeller\">{{cite web | url = https://www.nytimes.com/2019/05/30/us/census-citizenship-question-hofeller.html | title = Deceased G.O.P. Strategist's Hard Drives Reveal New Details on the Census Citizenship Question | first = Michael | last = Wines | date = May 30, 2019 | accessdate = May 31, 2019 | work = [[The New York Times]]}}</ref> Following this discovery, the [[United States House Committee on Oversight and Reform]] issued subpoenas for the Department of Justice to provide materials related to the census question and to question both Commerce Secretary Wilbur Ross and [[United States Attorney General]] [[William Barr]], seeking action to judge if they are in contempt. The Trump administration on June 12, 2019, asserted [[executive privilege]] over portions of the requested documents.<ref>{{cite web | url = https://www.cnn.com/2019/06/12/politics/house-oversight-contempt-vote-barr-ross/index.html | title = Trump invokes executive privilege ahead of House Oversight contempt vote for Barr, Ross | first1 = Clare | last1 =  Foran | first2 = Lauren | last2= Fox | date = June 12, 2019 | accessdate = June 12, 2019 | work = [[CNN]] }}</ref> As a result, the House Committee subsequently voted along party lines to hold both Ross and Barr in contempt that day.<ref>{{cite web | url = https://www.usatoday.com/story/news/politics/2019/06/12/house-oversight-barr-ross-contempt-defying-census-subpoenas/1433085001/  |title = House panel votes contempt for Attorney General William Barr and Commerce Secretary Wilbur Ross  |first=  Bart | last = Jansen | date = June 12, 2019 | accessdate = June 12, 2019  |work = [[USA Today]] }}</ref> The full House voted to hold Ross and Barr in contempt on July 17, 2019, in a 230\u2013198 vote along party lines. Despite this passage, the measure will likely not have any effect on Ross and Barr unless the Justice Department takes legal actions against Ross or Barr.<ref>{{cite web | url = https://www.cnn.com/2019/07/17/politics/house-contempt-vote-barr-ross-census/index.html | title = House votes to hold Barr, Ross in criminal contempt over census dispute | first1= Clare | last1 = Foran | first2= Ashley | last2= Killough | date = July 17, 2019 | accessdate = July 17, 2019 | work = [[CNN]] }}</ref>\n\n===New York District Court and subsequent Supreme Court case===\n{{seealso|Department of Commerce v. New York}}\nA lawsuit, led by New York state's attorney general [[Barbara Underwood]] and joined by seventeen other states, fifteen cities and other civil rights groups, was filed in the [[United States District Court for the Southern District of New York]]. During the discovery phase of the trial, new information came to light that Ross had had previous discussions with [[Steve Bannon]] before March 2018 with the intent to add the citizenship question, contradicting statements that he had made to Congress in March. This led District Judge [[Jesse M. Furman]] in September 2018 to ask that Ross clear a day in his schedule to give a deposition to the court related to the addition of the census question prior to the planned start of the trial in November.<ref>{{cite web | url = https://www.cbsnews.com/news/census-citizenship-controversy-likely-to-face-new-york-trial/ | title = Census citizenship controversy likely to face New York trial | date = September 15, 2018 | accessdate = November 16, 2018 | publisher = [[Associated Press]] | via = [[CBS News]] }}</ref>\n\nThe Trump administration filed a writ of ''[[mandamus]]'' to the [[Supreme Court of the United States|United States Supreme Court]], requesting that they postpone the trial, and also to defer any involvement with Ross until the start of the trial. The Supreme Court issued an order that allowed the trial ''United States Census Bureau v. State of New York'' to go forward, but agreed to postpone Ross's [[Deposition (law)|deposition]] until after the start of the trial.<ref>{{cite web | url = https://www.cbsnews.com/news/supreme-court-refuses-trump-administration-request-to-delay-trial-on-2020-census-citizenship-question/ | title = Supreme Court refuses Trump administration request to delay trial on 2020 census citizenship question | first = William | last = Hennessy Jr. | date = November 2, 2018 | accessdate = November 16, 2018 | publisher = [[Associated Press]] | via = [[CBS News]] }}</ref> The Supreme Court also agreed to treat the writ of ''mandamus'' as a writ of petition, and granted ''[[certiorari]]'' to review the question raised by the government of whether a district court can request deposition of a high-ranking executive branch official on a matter related to a trial before evidence has been presented.<ref name=\"reuters 2018-11-16\">{{cite web | url = https://www.reuters.com/article/us-usa-congress-subpoenas/house-republican-to-subpoena-ex-fbi-director-comey-former-ag-lynch-idUSKCN1NL2EF | title = Supreme Court to hear census citizenship question dispute | first = Lawrence | last =Hurley | date = November 16, 2018 | accessdate = November 16, 2018 | publisher = [[Reuters]] }}</ref>\n\nJudge Furman ruled in January 2019 that the addition of the citizenship question to the census was unlawful, stating that \"the decision to add a citizenship question to the 2020 Census\u2014even if it did not violate the Constitution itself\u2014was unlawful for a multitude of independent reasons and must be set aside.\"<ref>{{cite web | url =https://www.cnn.com/2019/01/15/politics/census-citizenship-new-york/index.html  |title= Federal judge strikes down effort to add citizenship question to Census | first1= Elizabeth | last1 = Hartfield | first2= Gregory | last2= Wallace | date = January 15, 2019 | accessdate= January 15, 2019 | work = [[CNN]] }}</ref> The Justice department filed a petition for writ of [[certiorari before judgment]] to have the case directly heard by the [[Supreme Court of the United States|Supreme Court]] and bypass the normal appeal that would have been heard by the [[United States Court of Appeals for the Second Circuit|Second Circuit]], given the pending deadline of June 2019 to publish the census forms. The Supreme Court accepted the petition related to Furman's ruling on February 15, 2019, a separate matter from the question of Ross's deposition, and the case's oral arguments were heard on April 23, 2019.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.msn.com/en-us/news/us/supreme-court-will-rule-on-trump-administrations-effort-to-add-question-on-citizenship-to-2020-census/ar-BBTEn6v?O|title=Supreme Court will rule on Trump administration's effort to add question on citizenship to 2020 Census|website=www.msn.com|access-date=February 15, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.cbsnews.com/news/supreme-court-hears-arguments-on-2020-census-citizenship-question/|title=Supreme Court hears arguments on 2020 census citizenship question|website=www.cbsnews.com|language=en-US|access-date=2019-05-29}}</ref>\n\nThe Supreme Court issued its decision on June 27, 2019, rejecting the Trump administration's stated rationale for including the question.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2019/06/27/us/politics/census-citizenship-question-supreme-court.html|title=Supreme Court Leaves Census Question on Citizenship in Doubt|first=Adam|last=Liptak|date=June 27, 2019|publisher=|newspaper=The New York Times}}</ref> While the Court majority agreed that the question was allowable under the Enumeration Act, they also agreed with the ability of the District Court to ask Commerce for further explanation for the question under the [[Administrative Procedure Act (United States)|Administrative Procedures Act]] (APA), and that they agreed with the District Court that the answers Commerce had provided at the time appeared to be \"contrived\" and pretextual, leaving open the possibility that Commerce could offer a better rationale.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2019/06/27/us/politics/census-citizenship-question-supreme-court.html|title=Supreme Court Leaves Census Question on Citizenship in Doubt|last=Liptak|first=Adam|date=2019-06-27|work=[[The New York Times]]|access-date=2019-06-27|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331}}</ref> The case was remanded back to the District Court, to give Commerce the opportunity to provide better explanation for the rationale of the question to the District Court, who would deem if that was sufficient before allowing the question on the census. The question would be allowed on the census only if these steps can be completed before the self-imposed form printing deadline.<ref>{{cite web | url = https://www.usatoday.com/story/news/politics/2019/06/27/2020-census-citizenship-question-supreme-court-avoids-trump-request/1289738001/  |title = Supreme Court orders further fact-finding on controversial 2020 census citizenship question | date = June 27, 2019 | accessdate= June 27, 2019  | work = [[USA Today]] }}</ref> On July 7 the DOJ announced that it was replacing its entire legal team dealing with that question, but on July 9 Furman rejected the DOJ action, saying that reasons must be given for the withdrawal of each attorney and pointing out that the administration had been insisting for months that the question needed to be settled by July 1.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Thomsen |first1=Jacqueline |title=Judge rejects Justice Dept request to pull lawyers from census case |url=https://thehill.com/regulation/court-battles/452288-judge-rejects-justice-dept-request-to-pull-lawyers-from-ny-census |publisher=The Hill |date=July 9, 2019}}</ref>\n\nThe [[American Civil Liberties Union]] (ACLU) has taken steps to introduce the Hofeller evidence into the New York case but it will not be heard until late 2019, after the Census forms are to be published.<ref name=\"thehill 20190625\"/> {{Update inline|date=January 2020}}\n\n===California District Court case===\nThe second suit over the census question came in the [[United States District Court for the Northern District of California]] under Judge [[Richard Seeborg]], raised by the state of California and several cities within it. In March 2019, Seeborg similarly found as Furman had in New York that the addition of the census question was unconstitutional and issued an injunction to block its use.<ref name=\"3 district\"/><ref>{{cite web | url = https://www.npr.org/2019/03/06/698886346/second-judge-blocks-trump-administrations-census-citizenship-question-plans | title = Second Judge Blocks Trump Administration's Census Citizenship Question Plans | first=  Hanso  | last=  Lo Wang | date = March 6, 2019 | accessdate = July 3, 2019 | work = [[NPR]] }}</ref> The government appealed to the [[United States Court of Appeals for the Ninth Circuit|Ninth Circuit]] before the Supreme Court remanded the case.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.brennancenter.org/our-work/court-cases/california-v-ross|title=California v. Ross|website=Brennan Center for Justice|language=en|access-date=2019-11-19}}</ref><ref name=\"cnn 20190709\"/>\n\n===Maryland District Court case===\nA similar question related to the intent of the question was raised by several immigrants-rights groups in the [[United States District Court for the District of Maryland]]. The case was overseen by Judge [[George J. Hazel]] in the District of Maryland. Hazel had found for the pro-immigration groups in April 2019, ruling that the addition of an immigration question to the Census was unconstitutional.<ref name=\"3 district\">{{cite web | url =https://www.cnn.com/2019/04/05/politics/census-citizenship-question-ruling/index.html | title = Third federal judge blocks census citizenship question | first1 = Ariane | last1 = de Vogue | first2= Elizabeth | last2= Hartfield | date = April 5, 2019 | accessdate = April 5, 2019 | work = [[CNN]] }}</ref> The government issued its appeal to the [[United States Court of Appeals for the Fourth Circuit|Fourth Circuit Court of Appeals]].\n\nThe new Hofeller evidence was presented to Hazel as the case was being heard on appeal during June 2019 at the Fourth Circuit. Hazel stated that the new evidence \"raises a substantial issue\" <ref>{{cite web | url = https://www.npr.org/2019/06/19/733583150/judges-order-sets-up-potential-new-block-against-census-citizenship-question | title = Judge's Order Sets Up Potential New Block Against Census Citizenship Question | first = Hansi | last = Lo Wong | date = June 19, 2019 | accessdate = June 20, 2019 | work = [[NPR]] }}</ref> On June 25, 2019, the Fourth Circuit remanded the case back to Hazel's District Court with the newly provided evidence, and to review if the additional evidence showed discriminatory intent. Should Hazel find such intent, it would be possible for him to place an injunction on the addition of the census question during a new discovery phase, regardless of the Supreme Court decision in ''Department of Commerce v. New York''. This action would effectively render the question moot since the Census forms would need to be published at this point without the citizenship question to meet the mailing deadlines.<ref name=\"thehill 20190625\">{{cite web | url = https://thehill.com/regulation/court-battles/450260-appeals-court-sends-census-question-case-to-lower-court | title = Appeals court sends census case to lower court to review discrimination claims | first = Jacqueline | last = Thomsen | date = June 25, 2019 | accessdate = June 25, 2019 | work = [[The Hill (website)|The Hill]] }}</ref>\n\n===Subsequent actions===\nPresident Trump, after the Supreme Court decision in ''Department of Commerce'' was announced, stated his intent to find a way to delay the census as long as possible so that the judicial matter could be resolved.<ref>{{cite web | url = https://www.usatoday.com/story/news/politics/2019/06/27/supreme-court-citizenship-question-trump-wants-delay-census/1581702001/ | title = Trump says he asked lawyers if census could be delayed after Supreme Court decision on citizenship question | first1 = Nicolas | last1 = Wu | first2= Richard | last2= Wolf | date = June 27, 2019 | accessdate = June 27, 2019 | work = [[USA Today]] }}</ref>\nOn July 2, 2019, the [[United States Department of Justice|Department of Justice]] (DOJ) announced that the citizenship question would not be included in the census, and the Commerce Department began printing census forms without a citizenship question.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Marimow |first1=Ann E. |last2=Bahrampour |first2=Tara |title=2020 Census will not include citizenship question, DOJ confirms |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/local/social-issues/2020-census-will-not-include-citizenship-question-doj-confirms/2019/07/02/0067be4a-9c44-11e9-9ed4-c9089972ad5a_story.html |work=Washington Post |date=2 July 2019 |language=en}}</ref> However, the next day, Trump insisted that his administration was \"absolutely moving forward\" with the citizenship question, and the Justice Department confirmed in court that it had been instructed to find a legal way to include it in the census.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Wang |first1=Hansi Lo |last2=Kelly |first2=Amita |title=DOJ Still Looking To Add Census Citizenship Question, Official Tells Court |url=https://www.npr.org/2019/07/03/738139549/trump-digs-in-on-census-citizenship-question-sparking-confusion-and-court-activi |work=NPR.org |date=July 3, 2019 | accessdate = July 3, 2019}}</ref><ref name=\"nytimes 20190703\">{{cite web | url = https://www.nytimes.com/2019/07/03/us/politics/census-citizenship-question.html | title = Justice Department Reverses Course on Citizenship Question on Census, Citing Trump's Orders  | first1 = Michael | last1 = Wines | first2=  Maggie | last2=  Haberman | first3=  Alan | last3 =  Rappeport | date = July 3, 2019 | accessdate = July 3, 2019 | work = [[The New York Times]] }}</ref>\n\nIn response to an order from Judge Hazel, the Justice Department affirmed on July 5, 2019 that it will be seeking a route to add the citizenship question to the census, though at the time did not know which route it would take. Hazel had ordered this response as, if the Department was intending to add the question, he could begin determining a schedule in coordination with Judge Furman in the New York court for further proceedings and discovery in both the New York and Maryland lawsuits.<ref name=\"nytimes 20190703\"/><ref>{{cite web | url = https://www.nytimes.com/2019/07/05/us/census-question.html | title = Trump Administration Pressing Ahead in Efforts to Add Citizenship Question to Census | first = Michael | last=  Wines | date = July 5, 2019 | accessdate = July 5, 2019  |work = [[The New York Times]] }}</ref> On July 7 the DOJ announced its intention to replace its entire legal team on the case,<ref>{{cite web | url = https://www.cnn.com/2019/07/07/politics/doj-new-legal-team-census/index.html | title = DOJ says new legal team will take over census case | first1 = Kaitlan | last1 = Collins | first2=  David | last2= Shortell | first3 = Kate | last3=  Sullivan | date = July 7, 2019 | accessdate = July 7, 2019 | work = [[CNN]] }}</ref> but Furman allowed the DOJ to dismiss only two of its eleven attorneys, writing in the July 9 rejection that the DOJ had \"provide[d] no reasons, let alone 'satisfactory reasons,' for the substitution of counsel\".<ref name=\"cnn 20190709\"/><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.huffpost.com/entry/census-citizenship-case-doj-attorneys_n_5d2509abe4b0cfb595fd62e8|title=Judge Blocks DOJ Request To Switch Lawyers In Census Citizenship Case|last=Levine|first=Sam|date=2019-07-09|website=HuffPost|language=en|access-date=2019-07-10}}</ref> Furman pointed out that the case had already run past the DOJ's own previously requested deadline of July 1 and that replacing counsel would cause further delays.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Thomsen |first1=Jacqueline |title=Judge rejects Justice Dept request to pull lawyers from census case |url=https://thehill.com/regulation/court-battles/452288-judge-rejects-justice-dept-request-to-pull-lawyers-from-ny-census | website = [[The Hill (magazine)|The Hill]] |date=July 9, 2019 | accessdate = July 9, 2019}}</ref><ref name=\"cnn 20190709\">{{cite web | url = https://www.cnn.com/2019/07/09/politics/federal-judge-doj-census-legal-team/index.html |title = Federal judge says DOJ can't swap out its legal team in census case | first = Katelyn | last = Polantz | date = July 9, 2019 | accessdate = July 9, 2019 | work = [[CNN]] }}</ref>\n\nSeparate from the events in the courts, Trump has stated he also considered using an [[executive order]] to place the citizenship question on the census.<ref>{{cite web | url = https://www.cnn.com/2019/07/11/politics/trump-census-executive-action/index.html | title = Trump expected to announce executive action on census | first1 = Jim | last1 = Acosta | first2= Joe | last2 = Johns | first3 = Gregory | last3 =  Wallace | date = July 11, 2019 | accessdate = July 11, 2019  |work = [[CNN]] }}</ref> However, on July 11 he issued Executive Order 13880 directing the Department of Commerce to obtain citizenship data from other federal agencies rather than via the census.<ref>{{cite news |title=Trump backs away from census citizenship question, direct agencies to hand over citizenship information to Commerce |url=https://www.cnn.com/2019/07/11/politics/trump-census-executive-action/index.html |accessdate=July 11, 2019 |issue=July 11, 2019 |publisher=CNN}}</ref> He added that \"we are not backing down in our effort to determine the citizenship status of the United States population\" and that data from other federal agencies would be \"far more accurate\" than a census question.<ref name = Re/> A spokesperson for the Department of Justice said that although the DOJ had agreed with Ross's plan to include the question, \"Today\u2019s Executive Order represents an alternative path to collecting the best citizenship data now available, which is vital for informed policymaking and numerous other reasons.  Accordingly, the Department will promptly inform the courts that the Government will not include a citizenship question on the 2020 decennial census.\u201d<ref name = Re>{{cite news |last1=Re |first1=Gregg |title=Trump, 'not backing down' in effort to count citizens amid census fight, announces executive order |url=https://www.foxnews.com/politics/trump-citizens-executive-order-census-count |accessdate=July 11, 2019 |publisher=Fox News |date=July 11, 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Notes==\n{{notelist}}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* [https://census.gov/2020census/ 2020 Census] from the [[United States Census Bureau]]\n\n{{USCensus}}\n\n[[Category:United States Census]]\n[[Category:Trump administration controversies]]\n[[Category:2020 in American politics|Census 2020]]\n[[Category:2020 censuses|United States]]\n", "name_user": "2600:8800:9280:679:29bb:d77d:15bb:4cdf", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "(\u2192\u200eNotes)", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/2020_United_States_Census"}
